00:02:30.120 --> 00:02:33.920
[Amit Varma]: Ram, in the last episode, we spoke about Gandhi before India.

00:02:33.920 --> 00:02:37.520
[Amit Varma]: Before we really get further into today's episode, I'd like to speak a little bit about

00:02:37.520 --> 00:02:39.180
[Amit Varma]: Guha before Gandhi.

00:02:39.180 --> 00:02:40.600
[Guest]: How did you become a historian?

00:02:40.600 --> 00:02:43.600
[Guest]: Well, there is a chapter accidents.

00:02:43.600 --> 00:02:50.800
[Guest]: So you know, I grew up wanting to play cricket and I did science in school.

00:02:50.800 --> 00:02:53.920
[Guest]: But I knew that if you do science in college, you have practicals in the afternoon, you

00:02:53.920 --> 00:02:56.080
[Guest]: can't get the college cricket team.

00:02:56.080 --> 00:02:57.080
[Guest]: So I registered for economics.

00:02:57.080 --> 00:03:01.800
[Guest]: I was interested in writing, I did for the school magazine, my high school magazine.

00:03:01.800 --> 00:03:06.280
[Guest]: And if I'd had guts, I would have gone and done a BA in English literature, but I didn't

00:03:06.280 --> 00:03:11.240
[Guest]: have the guts because I came from a family of scientists and literature was a stretch

00:03:11.240 --> 00:03:12.240
[Guest]: too far.

00:03:12.240 --> 00:03:13.240
[Guest]: It is economics being a kind of pseudoscience.

00:03:13.240 --> 00:03:18.440
[Guest]: Let me tell you a joke about economics as a pseudoscience, which is told by the great

00:03:18.440 --> 00:03:20.880
[Guest]: historian of Islam, Bernard Lewis.

00:03:20.880 --> 00:03:30.000
[Guest]: And he says that in the history of humankind, science is often emerged out of magic.

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:37.040
[Guest]: From astrology came astronomy, from alchemy came chemistry, what will come out of economics?

00:03:37.040 --> 00:03:43.640
[Guest]: Okay, so it's at least a pseudoscience and it sort of placated my parents and my grandparents.

00:03:43.640 --> 00:03:46.200
[Guest]: And but I was spectacularly useless at economics.

00:03:46.200 --> 00:03:50.840
[Guest]: I did a BA, did an MA, I took a gap, what's now called a gap year, looked around.

00:03:50.840 --> 00:03:54.400
[Guest]: And in that gap year, I discovered the works of the anthropologist Verrier Elwin and was

00:03:54.400 --> 00:03:57.000
[Guest]: lucky enough to get a PhD admission in sociology.

00:03:57.000 --> 00:03:58.880
[Guest]: So economics was moving me.

00:03:58.880 --> 00:04:02.640
[Guest]: So essentially, economics is really abstract and analytical and mathematical.

00:04:02.640 --> 00:04:08.520
[Guest]: Sociology is about human beings, but in society and with kind of an overlay of structures

00:04:08.520 --> 00:04:09.840
[Guest]: determining them.

00:04:09.840 --> 00:04:13.160
[Guest]: And then from there, I moved to history, which is process and then finally to biography,

00:04:13.160 --> 00:04:15.860
[Guest]: which is actually a single individual life.

00:04:15.860 --> 00:04:20.040
[Guest]: But my degrees are really in economics and sociology and it was in the course of my research

00:04:20.040 --> 00:04:24.880
[Guest]: on really environmental subjects that I got interested in the history of forests and then

00:04:24.880 --> 00:04:28.640
[Guest]: I fell in love with the archives and the joy of discovering old documents nobody has ever

00:04:28.640 --> 00:04:33.160
[Guest]: seen before and pouring over them to consume me.

00:04:33.160 --> 00:04:35.480
[Amit Varma]: And I kind of became an accidental historian.

00:04:35.480 --> 00:04:39.400
[Amit Varma]: And you've written somewhere about how, you know, in 1998, I think it was and you were

00:04:39.400 --> 00:04:43.220
[Amit Varma]: really known as someone who's written books on environmental history and so on.

00:04:43.220 --> 00:04:46.960
[Amit Varma]: And I think it was in New York where you were asked, would you give a class on something

00:04:46.960 --> 00:04:47.960
[Amit Varma]: in Berkeley?

00:04:47.960 --> 00:04:48.960
[Amit Varma]: In Berkeley?

00:04:48.960 --> 00:04:49.960
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:04:49.960 --> 00:04:54.680
[Amit Varma]: And instead of choosing environmentalism as your subject, you picked Gandhi, why?

00:04:54.680 --> 00:05:00.080
[Guest]: So I'd been, I'd started reading around Gandhi, I mean, you know, as what happened was, I'd

00:05:00.080 --> 00:05:02.600
[Guest]: been working on the environment.

00:05:02.600 --> 00:05:05.920
[Guest]: And my first book was a history of the Chipko movement and the two great leaders of the

00:05:05.920 --> 00:05:09.960
[Guest]: Chipko movement, both fortunately alive, both in the late 80s, Tandir Prasad Bhatt and Sundar

00:05:09.960 --> 00:05:14.400
[Guest]: Lal Bahguna, kind of exemplified the best kind of living Gandhianism.

00:05:14.400 --> 00:05:20.420
[Guest]: They were men of transparency, integrity, moral courage, nonviolent, you know, innovatively

00:05:20.420 --> 00:05:23.560
[Guest]: using Gandhian methods to protect the Himalayan forests.

00:05:23.560 --> 00:05:25.120
[Guest]: And so I started reading about Gandhi.

00:05:25.120 --> 00:05:30.600
[Guest]: I mean, those days, when I'm talking about the 70s and the 80s, I don't travel much by

00:05:30.600 --> 00:05:31.600
[Guest]: train anymore.

00:05:31.600 --> 00:05:33.600
[Guest]: So it's probably, but I'm sure it's not the case.

00:05:33.600 --> 00:05:38.680
[Guest]: In the 70s and the 80s, you had these railway bookstores with A. H. Wheeler, and they often

00:05:38.680 --> 00:05:41.600
[Guest]: had books published by Navjeevan.

00:05:41.600 --> 00:05:49.800
[Guest]: And just in the 80s and 90s, I picked up a large number of books all about Gandhi.

00:05:49.800 --> 00:05:52.880
[Guest]: And there were two books that profoundly struck me.

00:05:52.880 --> 00:05:57.280
[Guest]: One was a book edited by an anthologist called R. K. Prabhu, it's called Truth, Call Them

00:05:57.280 --> 00:06:01.800
[Guest]: Differently, which is about the correspondence between Tagore and Gandhi over a long period.

00:06:01.800 --> 00:06:07.880
[Guest]: And the other is a book called An Atheist with Gandhi, which was by a Andhra social

00:06:07.880 --> 00:06:12.160
[Guest]: reformer who worked on the emancipation of Dalits called Gora Ramchandra Rao, G. Ramchandra

00:06:12.160 --> 00:06:14.160
[Guest]: Rao, known as Gora.

00:06:14.160 --> 00:06:16.720
[Guest]: And I got more interested in Gandhi outside the environment.

00:06:16.720 --> 00:06:21.520
[Guest]: You know, Gandhi as a thinker on religion, morality, civilization.

00:06:21.520 --> 00:06:25.960
[Guest]: And then I read Ambedkar's great book, Annihilation of Caste, which is, of course, also a fantastic

00:06:25.960 --> 00:06:26.960
[Guest]: polemic against Gandhi.

00:06:26.960 --> 00:06:32.320
[Guest]: And then I came up against some of the limitations of Gandhi's whole social reform movement.

00:06:32.320 --> 00:06:37.160
[Guest]: And it was really these three tracks, Ambedkar's Annihilation of Caste, Gora's book An Atheist

00:06:37.160 --> 00:06:43.320
[Guest]: with Gandhi, and this collection of the letters between Tagore and Gandhi, that moved me towards

00:06:43.320 --> 00:06:45.480
[Guest]: thinking maybe I should teach a course on Gandhi.

00:06:45.480 --> 00:06:46.480
[Guest]: I'm bored with the environment.

00:06:46.480 --> 00:06:47.480
[Guest]: So I went to Berkeley.

00:06:47.480 --> 00:06:50.720
[Guest]: And then that course worked out incredibly well.

00:06:50.720 --> 00:06:54.680
[Guest]: And I had students of very different backgrounds, different nationalities.

00:06:54.680 --> 00:06:59.320
[Guest]: There was a Burmese student, a Japanese student, an African-American student.

00:06:59.320 --> 00:07:02.160
[Guest]: And ever since, I've been kind of consumed with Gandhi.

00:07:02.160 --> 00:07:07.680
[Amit Varma]: And you know, since you initially got attracted to Gandhianism, which, of course, is a distillation

00:07:07.680 --> 00:07:10.240
[Amit Varma]: of his best ideas and values that survive.

00:07:10.240 --> 00:07:14.800
[Amit Varma]: And you actually wrote these books on the man himself with all his complexities and,

00:07:14.800 --> 00:07:16.960
[Amit Varma]: you know, all the dark sides and so on.

00:07:16.960 --> 00:07:21.480
[Amit Varma]: How did you come to look at Gandhi and Gandhianism differently?

00:07:21.480 --> 00:07:27.000
[Guest]: So I mean, I think we discussed some of this in the, you know, in the first episode.

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:33.920
[Guest]: I think Gandhi, if you look at Gandhi in the context of the India of today, I think clearly

00:07:33.920 --> 00:07:39.640
[Guest]: interfaith harmony, relations of mutual respect, accommodation between Hindus and Muslims are

00:07:39.640 --> 00:07:44.040
[Guest]: of yet still of crucial importance, though, you know, the ruling classes today kind of

00:07:44.040 --> 00:07:47.440
[Guest]: denied and want to move us more and more in the direction of a Hindu state.

00:07:47.440 --> 00:07:51.480
[Guest]: I mean, today's newspaper talks about the citizenship bill, which will give, you know,

00:07:51.480 --> 00:07:56.520
[Guest]: citizenship rights to anyone who's a Hindu from anywhere, basically, is what he says,

00:07:56.520 --> 00:07:57.520
[Guest]: right?

00:07:57.520 --> 00:07:59.560
[Amit Varma]: Which is kind of a denial of Gandhi's more universalistic philosophy.

00:07:59.560 --> 00:08:05.200
[Guest]: We're recording on Jan 8, by the way.

00:08:05.200 --> 00:08:12.360
[Guest]: The other thing, Amit, is that, look, for Gandhi, Hinduism was fallible.

00:08:12.360 --> 00:08:16.840
[Guest]: So every religion, every national tradition was fallible.

00:08:16.840 --> 00:08:19.640
[Guest]: You looked in the mirror of the other and improved yourself.

00:08:19.640 --> 00:08:23.680
[Guest]: Hinduism was fallible because we treated our untouchables and our women badly, right?

00:08:23.680 --> 00:08:27.280
[Guest]: India was fallible because, you know, our institutions didn't work well.

00:08:27.280 --> 00:08:29.280
[Guest]: Of course, in those days, there wasn't that much corruption.

00:08:29.280 --> 00:08:35.840
[Guest]: I think this understanding of Gandhi that individuals are fallible, cultures are fallible,

00:08:35.840 --> 00:08:40.960
[Guest]: communities are fallible, religious traditions are fallible, nations are fallible, I think

00:08:40.960 --> 00:08:48.800
[Guest]: is vitally important today, which is kind of an absolute lack of respect for criticisms

00:08:48.800 --> 00:08:51.000
[Guest]: of religions or communities or individuals.

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:56.600
[Guest]: I mean, Modi is infallible, Hinduism is infallible, Bharat Mata is infallible, you know, that

00:08:56.600 --> 00:08:58.080
[Amit Varma]: is completely contrary to Gandhi's teaching.

00:08:58.080 --> 00:09:01.800
[Amit Varma]: In fact, we think it absolutes today, but you know, as we'll probably discuss later

00:09:01.800 --> 00:09:06.360
[Amit Varma]: in the episode, to some extent, Gandhi also did, he was dogmatic about a lot of things,

00:09:06.360 --> 00:09:09.840
[Amit Varma]: but we'll kind of come to that.

00:09:09.840 --> 00:09:14.000
[Amit Varma]: So your book, Gandhi, The Years That Changed The World, really takes us, begins where your

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:18.920
[Amit Varma]: last book ended, Gandhi Before India, where he's arrived back in India, and he's just

00:09:18.920 --> 00:09:22.360
[Amit Varma]: chatted with his mentor and someone he really admired, Gopal Krishna Gokhale.

00:09:22.360 --> 00:09:26.480
[Amit Varma]: And Gokhale told him that, look, for a year, I just want you to go around the country,

00:09:26.480 --> 00:09:29.480
[Amit Varma]: don't open your mouth, don't give opinions, and so on and so forth.

00:09:29.480 --> 00:09:31.440
[Guest]: Why do you think Gokhale gave him this advice?

00:09:31.440 --> 00:09:35.720
[Guest]: I think Gokhale gave him that advice, because he'd been away for so long, he'd been away

00:09:35.720 --> 00:09:40.760
[Guest]: from India for 22 years, and he didn't understand the landscape.

00:09:40.760 --> 00:09:43.200
[Guest]: Even when he was in India, all he knew was Gujarat and Bombay.

00:09:43.200 --> 00:09:48.840
[Guest]: I mean, he'd been to Calcutta once for a Congress, he'd been to Madras once to address a meeting,

00:09:48.840 --> 00:09:55.360
[Guest]: he'd been to Pune once, but I think Gokhale thought that he must understand the country

00:09:55.360 --> 00:09:57.720
[Guest]: he's going to spend the rest of his life in.

00:09:57.720 --> 00:10:01.440
[Guest]: The other reason, though, it's probably not spelled out by Gokhale, was Gokhale, we again

00:10:01.440 --> 00:10:05.920
[Guest]: discussed in the first episode, Hind Swaraj, Gokhale was profoundly ambivalent about Hind

00:10:05.920 --> 00:10:06.920
[Guest]: Swaraj.

00:10:06.920 --> 00:10:12.300
[Guest]: He thought it an ideologically utopian fact, and he perhaps felt that if Gandhi was to

00:10:12.300 --> 00:10:16.800
[Guest]: come be confronted with ground realities in India, he would nuance and modify some of

00:10:16.800 --> 00:10:18.360
[Guest]: the extreme positions he took in Hind Swaraj.

00:10:18.360 --> 00:10:19.720
[Guest]: In fact, that's exactly what happened.

00:10:19.720 --> 00:10:24.560
[Guest]: And I think it was very wise advice for him, and he traveled all over, I mean, he would

00:10:24.560 --> 00:10:29.320
[Guest]: just track his journeys in those days, and train travel was incredibly arduous in those

00:10:29.320 --> 00:10:30.320
[Guest]: days.

00:10:30.320 --> 00:10:31.320
[Guest]: He often went with Kasturba.

00:10:31.320 --> 00:10:33.980
[Guest]: Many of those journeys were with Kasturba, some were alone.

00:10:33.980 --> 00:10:37.720
[Guest]: But he went north, south, east, west, he went to Shantiniketan, he went to Banaras, he went

00:10:37.720 --> 00:10:43.080
[Guest]: to Gurukul Kangri, he came to Madras, he went deep south to places like Mayavaram and Tirunelveli

00:10:43.080 --> 00:10:47.720
[Guest]: where he was confronted with the horrors of untouchability for the first time in a direct

00:10:47.720 --> 00:10:48.720
[Guest]: way.

00:10:48.720 --> 00:10:55.600
[Guest]: He traveled through his native Kathiawar, up and down, Gondal, Porbandar, Rajkot, Wadawan

00:10:55.600 --> 00:10:56.600
[Guest]: and so on.

00:10:56.600 --> 00:11:02.560
[Guest]: And I think he came to understand this country he had come back to and whose politics he

00:11:02.560 --> 00:11:03.560
[Guest]: wanted to immerse himself in.

00:11:03.560 --> 00:11:08.120
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, in your book, you mentioned that he was also asked to give opinions on something

00:11:08.120 --> 00:11:10.360
[Amit Varma]: or speak about something during this period.

00:11:10.360 --> 00:11:15.160
[Amit Varma]: But even though Gokhale had died a month into this journey, he respected the promise he

00:11:15.160 --> 00:11:16.160
[Guest]: had made.

00:11:16.160 --> 00:11:17.160
[Guest]: Absolutely.

00:11:17.160 --> 00:11:23.360
[Guest]: And it's only his, you know, voluntary vow of silence on political and social matters

00:11:23.360 --> 00:11:28.480
[Guest]: was in January 1916, that vow was no longer valid.

00:11:28.480 --> 00:11:32.000
[Guest]: And it's only then that he started speaking, of course, the most, his coming out speech

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:37.280
[Guest]: is in Banaras when he attacks the Indian elite for their luxurious lifestyles, their jewelry

00:11:37.280 --> 00:11:40.440
[Guest]: and the craven worship of the colonial ethos and so on.

00:11:40.440 --> 00:11:42.800
[Amit Varma]: But it's a full year before he speaks up.

00:11:42.800 --> 00:11:48.360
[Amit Varma]: And it's interesting that in a sense, he is now faced with the challenge of making once

00:11:48.360 --> 00:11:52.520
[Amit Varma]: again, a particular journey that he had already made in the sense when he went to South Africa,

00:11:52.520 --> 00:11:56.720
[Amit Varma]: when he began campaigning for the Indians there, he was a representative of the elites,

00:11:56.720 --> 00:12:02.400
[Amit Varma]: which is the Gujarati merchants and the Parsis and not the laborers at that point in time.

00:12:02.400 --> 00:12:06.960
[Amit Varma]: But then he turned it into within the limited scope of the Indians that were in South Africa,

00:12:06.960 --> 00:12:11.280
[Amit Varma]: what you could call a bit of a mass movement, where all the Tamilians came on board, and

00:12:11.280 --> 00:12:12.640
[Amit Varma]: so on and so forth.

00:12:12.640 --> 00:12:16.120
[Amit Varma]: And now, as you point out at the start of this book, he shifted from an arena where

00:12:16.120 --> 00:12:21.800
[Amit Varma]: there are 150,000 Indians to an arena where there are 300 million Indians, and the movement

00:12:21.800 --> 00:12:26.240
[Amit Varma]: as it was in his early days in South Africa, is really an elite movement still, can you

00:12:26.240 --> 00:12:29.840
[Amit Varma]: lay out the landscape for me at the time, like, what is the freedom movement like?

00:12:29.840 --> 00:12:34.960
[Guest]: So what there is the Indian National Congress, which is now 30 years old, by the time as

00:12:34.960 --> 00:12:40.560
[Guest]: Gandhi has come, it's clearly grown quite substantially in numbers, it's had a meeting

00:12:40.560 --> 00:12:45.000
[Guest]: every year, its membership has expanded.

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:48.560
[Guest]: Several years before Gandhi comes in 1907, there's a major split in the Congress between

00:12:48.560 --> 00:12:54.600
[Guest]: the extremists and the moderates, the extremists, led by Tilak, who want militant action now,

00:12:54.600 --> 00:12:58.720
[Guest]: the moderates led by Gokhale, who feel not only that you can appeal to the better instincts

00:12:58.720 --> 00:13:02.960
[Guest]: of the British through reason and argument, but also that social reform is crucial, whereas

00:13:02.960 --> 00:13:08.760
[Guest]: the extremists led by Tilak felt, feel that social reform will come after political independence.

00:13:08.760 --> 00:13:12.800
[Guest]: So there's a split. And when Gandhi comes back, there's an attempt to heal this split.

00:13:12.800 --> 00:13:16.840
[Guest]: Tilak has returned, he was in jail in Mandalay, he's come back, and there's an attempt to

00:13:16.840 --> 00:13:22.400
[Guest]: heal the split and bring the moderates and extremists on one platform.

00:13:22.400 --> 00:13:27.020
[Guest]: The other split that has happened in the Congress from the time it started is that when it started,

00:13:27.020 --> 00:13:32.280
[Guest]: it was both Hindu and Muslim intellectuals and aristocrats were in it. It was an elite

00:13:32.280 --> 00:13:38.000
[Guest]: organization, but it had both Hindu and Muslim elites. This changed, I mean, Syed Ahmed Khan

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:42.760
[Guest]: moved away from the Congress, many Muslims moved away. In 1906, the Muslim League was

00:13:42.760 --> 00:13:47.920
[Guest]: formed and there's an attempt in Gandhi's first years in India to bring Muslims back.

00:13:47.920 --> 00:13:53.520
[Guest]: So in 1916, which is a year after Gandhi comes back, there's a meeting in Lucknow of the

00:13:53.520 --> 00:13:57.120
[Guest]: Congress, which Gandhi attends, where Jinnah and Tilak forge a kind of compact between

00:13:57.120 --> 00:14:00.160
[Guest]: the Congress and the Muslim League. Now, what is interesting is that Gandhi attends the

00:14:00.160 --> 00:14:04.800
[Guest]: 1915 Congress in Bombay, the Congress in those days, the annual Congress was held in December

00:14:04.800 --> 00:14:09.800
[Guest]: in those days. End of his first year, he attends that Congress. End of the second year, he

00:14:09.800 --> 00:14:14.600
[Guest]: attends the Lucknow Congress. And in both places, he's a marginal figure. All he's allowed

00:14:14.600 --> 00:14:20.880
[Guest]: to speak on is indentured labor in South Africa. He can't speak on political reform, constitutional

00:14:20.880 --> 00:14:26.480
[Guest]: change, Hindu-Muslim collaboration, none of these issues. He's really a marginal figure

00:14:26.480 --> 00:14:31.800
[Guest]: who's on, you know, in kind of some small hall somewhere in an obscure part of the big

00:14:31.800 --> 00:14:37.640
[Guest]: conference. The great leaders are Annie Besant, Malviya, Tilak, Jinnah, you know, and so on

00:14:37.640 --> 00:14:42.080
[Guest]: and so forth. Gokhale, of course, dies shortly after Gandhi comes back. And Bipin Chandrapal,

00:14:42.080 --> 00:14:48.480
[Guest]: you know, Lajpat Rai, and they're the kind of leaders of the Congress at that stage.

00:14:48.480 --> 00:14:53.360
[Guest]: And he really is a very marginal figure. But he knows he's looking for his chance. I mean,

00:14:53.360 --> 00:14:59.840
[Guest]: I think Gandhi is a person of great ambition. We briefly alluded to this in our first episode.

00:14:59.840 --> 00:15:05.720
[Guest]: He comes back from South Africa because he wants to claim a larger stage. He wants for

00:15:05.720 --> 00:15:11.120
[Guest]: himself a greater historic role. It's not in his, he has proved to himself that he can

00:15:11.120 --> 00:15:17.920
[Guest]: lead 150,000 diasporic Indians in South Africa. And at some level, he's bored and disenchanted

00:15:17.920 --> 00:15:23.040
[Guest]: with this. He wants to move on to bigger things. And he comes back. But clearly he's patient.

00:15:23.040 --> 00:15:28.520
[Guest]: Gokhale has told him to understand the country. He tours for a year. He starts speaking briefly

00:15:28.520 --> 00:15:36.920
[Guest]: on these issues. 1915-16, he's on the margins. And the first major opportunity comes in 1917

00:15:36.920 --> 00:15:42.080
[Guest]: when he goes to Champaran and gets involved in, you know, the struggle of the Indigo tenants

00:15:42.080 --> 00:15:46.160
[Guest]: there. And he comes face to face with agrarian distress, what we would today call agrarian

00:15:46.160 --> 00:15:53.040
[Guest]: distress, right? And in a way in which neither Tilak, nor Gokhale, nor Jinnah, nor any Besant,

00:15:53.040 --> 00:15:57.560
[Guest]: nor any of the leaders of Congress had ever had a clue of how the peasants lived and labored.

00:15:57.560 --> 00:16:03.320
[Guest]: And Gandhi, in those three months in Champaran, understands that the real problem of India

00:16:03.320 --> 00:16:11.160
[Guest]: is, lies outside the cities. And if India is to really, you know, if a political action

00:16:11.160 --> 00:16:16.600
[Guest]: in India must bring in peasants, which the Congress till that stage has not been able

00:16:16.600 --> 00:16:17.600
[Amit Varma]: to do.

00:16:17.600 --> 00:16:21.160
[Amit Varma]: So before we talk further about Champaran, which I want to do, just a thought that struck

00:16:21.160 --> 00:16:25.000
[Amit Varma]: me when you spoke about Gandhi's ambition, and it's probably an outrageous question,

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:31.400
[Amit Varma]: but do you think that self-delusion is a necessary condition to attain greatness? What I mean

00:16:31.400 --> 00:16:35.640
[Amit Varma]: by that is no one starts out great, you know, and people always imagine themselves to be

00:16:35.640 --> 00:16:42.000
[Amit Varma]: more than they are at the time, and some people overreach and fall flat, but some people just

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:45.560
[Amit Varma]: keep going driven by their delusion till they actually achieve greatness.

00:16:45.560 --> 00:16:50.960
[Guest]: Well, I would rather call it self-belief. I mean, the belief may be delusory. In many

00:16:50.960 --> 00:16:56.360
[Guest]: cases, it may be delusory, you know, that actually you may get nowhere in your career.

00:16:56.360 --> 00:17:01.200
[Guest]: But self-belief is, Gandhi clearly had it. He had it from an early age. It was confirmed

00:17:01.200 --> 00:17:05.440
[Guest]: by his associates in South Africa, his friend Ranjeevan Mehta, who announced him a Mahatma

00:17:05.440 --> 00:17:11.480
[Guest]: well before Tagore does and so on. But I think the only explanation for Gandhi leaving South

00:17:11.480 --> 00:17:15.480
[Guest]: Africa and coming back to India is that he wants to be the leader of all of India. He's

00:17:15.480 --> 00:17:20.000
[Guest]: not content with being the leader of a small expatriate community.

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:25.040
[Amit Varma]: And in some sense, much as the death of Gokhale is a shock to him, does it also free him in

00:17:25.040 --> 00:17:26.040
[Guest]: some way?

00:17:26.040 --> 00:17:31.640
[Guest]: Very much so, very much so. So I think Gokhale was a kind of person he enormously venerated.

00:17:31.640 --> 00:17:34.880
[Guest]: So Gokhale wasn't that much older than him. He was only three years older than Gandhi

00:17:34.880 --> 00:17:40.400
[Guest]: in terms of calendar years. But in terms of political career, he had achieved eminence

00:17:40.400 --> 00:17:45.840
[Guest]: far before Gandhi. And his death does free him because Gokhale would probably have wanted

00:17:45.840 --> 00:17:50.320
[Guest]: him to stay within the servants of Indian society, focus on social reform, not really

00:17:50.320 --> 00:17:55.680
[Guest]: go out and work among the peasantry, let alone, you know, craft programs of All India Satyagraha.

00:17:55.680 --> 00:18:02.800
[Guest]: I mean, it's hard to say, but Gokhale was just short of 50 when he died. So, you know,

00:18:02.800 --> 00:18:08.160
[Guest]: if he lived another 10 years, I think Gandhi's career may not have blossomed in the way it

00:18:08.160 --> 00:18:09.160
[Amit Varma]: did.

00:18:09.160 --> 00:18:14.160
[Amit Varma]: And in the last episode, we discussed how so often consequential events are contingent,

00:18:14.160 --> 00:18:17.320
[Amit Varma]: you know, lucky things happen. Like in this case, while reading your book, what struck

00:18:17.320 --> 00:18:22.400
[Amit Varma]: me is you, you talk about someone from Champaran, Rajkumar Shukla, who went to the Congress

00:18:22.400 --> 00:18:26.440
[Amit Varma]: meetings and he tried to speak to the big leaders and get them to come to Champaran.

00:18:26.440 --> 00:18:30.680
[Amit Varma]: They showed absolutely no interest. And as you point out, Gandhi was kind of marginal

00:18:30.680 --> 00:18:34.120
[Amit Varma]: and he approached Gandhi once and Gandhi said, no, I'm not interested. He approached Gandhi

00:18:34.120 --> 00:18:38.600
[Amit Varma]: twice. Gandhi said no. And then he followed Gandhi all the way to Ahmedabad. Yeah. And

00:18:38.600 --> 00:18:42.920
[Amit Varma]: then finally Gandhi like, okay, whatever, you know, let's check it out. It kind of happened

00:18:42.920 --> 00:18:47.360
[Amit Varma]: like that, that he, you know, it wasn't as if he was seeking to discover what agrarian

00:18:47.360 --> 00:18:52.080
[Amit Varma]: crisis is like. He just gave in to the persistent demands of the gentleman and went along to

00:18:52.080 --> 00:18:55.240
[Amit Varma]: Champaran and then he saw what was happening and got involved.

00:18:55.240 --> 00:18:58.720
[Guest]: Yeah. And then he, once he got involved, he was incredibly excited. I mean, there's some

00:18:58.720 --> 00:19:02.400
[Guest]: letter I quote, I think it's to Pollack where he says, I'm reliving the excitement of my

00:19:02.400 --> 00:19:07.600
[Guest]: South African days. You know, I have my Kachalia, I have my so-and-so, I'm looking for my Pollack

00:19:07.600 --> 00:19:13.880
[Guest]: and my, and so on. And because he'd been three years away from political action and Champaran

00:19:13.880 --> 00:19:20.160
[Guest]: gave him this opportunity to craft a movement, to represent people, to become their spokesman,

00:19:20.160 --> 00:19:25.600
[Guest]: to mediate between them and the ruling authorities. You know, he became a hero in his native Gujarat

00:19:25.600 --> 00:19:31.160
[Guest]: because he disobeyed the deportation order that was issued to him and so on and so forth.

00:19:31.160 --> 00:19:37.000
[Guest]: So I think Champaran is that way very important. You know, people in Champaran make today have

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:41.440
[Guest]: this criticism of Gandhi, which is a legitimate criticism that we launched him on his political

00:19:41.440 --> 00:19:46.040
[Guest]: career and then he abandoned us. You know, he didn't really come back hard to Champaran

00:19:46.040 --> 00:19:50.360
[Guest]: and find out what was going on. But in the larger history of Indian nationalism, Champaran

00:19:50.360 --> 00:19:54.380
[Guest]: is a very important milestone. And just because of the role it played in Gandhi's life.

00:19:54.380 --> 00:19:57.600
[Amit Varma]: And just to fill my listeners in what was happening in Champaran was it was, there was

00:19:57.600 --> 00:20:02.960
[Amit Varma]: basically an agitation by indigo farmers because, because of the world war demand for indigo

00:20:02.960 --> 00:20:07.980
[Amit Varma]: had shot up. So, you know, the British wanted much more indigo. And one of the particularly

00:20:07.980 --> 00:20:13.840
[Amit Varma]: problematic clauses was that they insisted that poor peasants had to devote a certain

00:20:13.840 --> 00:20:20.160
[Amit Varma]: percentage, I think 10% of their land to, you know, planting indigo among various other

00:20:20.160 --> 00:20:24.800
[Amit Varma]: clauses, which were coercive and just flat out wrong. And what Gandhi did when he got

00:20:24.800 --> 00:20:29.960
[Amit Varma]: there was that he essentially traveled around the place and collected tens of thousands

00:20:29.960 --> 00:20:35.040
[Amit Varma]: of signatures and then petitioned the government successfully. And he won that particular battle.

00:20:35.040 --> 00:20:39.920
[Guest]: Yeah. Yeah. I mean, substantially, he won that battle that the onerous restrictions

00:20:39.920 --> 00:20:44.360
[Guest]: were removed by a lot. And it, you know, it also gave him a chance to understand the colonial

00:20:44.360 --> 00:20:49.520
[Guest]: state and its functioning apart from coming face to face with agrarian distress and how

00:20:49.520 --> 00:20:54.160
[Guest]: peasants lived and labored. It gave him this understanding of the mechanics of the colonial

00:20:54.160 --> 00:20:57.280
[Guest]: regime, which of course he was later to use to good effect.

00:20:57.280 --> 00:21:00.960
[Amit Varma]: And also like you mentioned that letter where he writes to Pollack, where he says that I

00:21:00.960 --> 00:21:04.800
[Amit Varma]: will find my tambi Naidu here and I will find so and so here. And it's very interesting

00:21:04.800 --> 00:21:08.940
[Amit Varma]: that during this period of time, Champaran and the year that follows, he finds a lot

00:21:08.940 --> 00:21:13.960
[Amit Varma]: of people who were his close associates through the years that follow, like in Champaran J.B.

00:21:13.960 --> 00:21:18.760
[Amit Varma]: Kripalani, then Rajinder Prasad, then as news of it got back to Gujarat, you know, Vallabhbhai

00:21:18.760 --> 00:21:23.560
[Amit Varma]: Patel approached him there. And you can see this group of people now building around him,

00:21:23.560 --> 00:21:27.440
[Amit Varma]: recognizing him as a leader through the sheer moral force of his actions.

00:21:27.440 --> 00:21:31.200
[Guest]: Absolutely. And the moral force and the moral courage. I mean, apart from the names you

00:21:31.200 --> 00:21:37.640
[Guest]: mentioned, I think Mahadev Desai, who was to be his lifelong companion, secretary, interlocutor,

00:21:37.640 --> 00:21:42.880
[Guest]: advisor, right hand man, left hand man, also joins in the same year, 1917. So 1917 is very,

00:21:42.880 --> 00:21:43.880
[Guest]: very important.

00:21:43.880 --> 00:21:49.120
[Amit Varma]: And tactically, how did the British approach Gandhi? Did they take him seriously?

00:21:49.120 --> 00:21:53.280
[Guest]: I think they were puzzled. I mean, the British were intrigued and puzzled. I mean, some clearly

00:21:53.280 --> 00:21:58.880
[Guest]: saw him as an unscrupulous agitator out there to create mischief. But there are several

00:21:58.880 --> 00:22:05.120
[Guest]: others. I think he's called Haycock. He's a district magistrate who says he's a yogi

00:22:05.120 --> 00:22:09.680
[Guest]: of the type, not unknown in the East, through his asceticism and his simple lifestyle, impresses

00:22:09.680 --> 00:22:13.840
[Guest]: and moves people. So clearly, some of them were very impressed. Some of them were hostile

00:22:13.840 --> 00:22:18.960
[Guest]: and angry. And this stroke of ambivalence runs right through the British reaction to

00:22:18.960 --> 00:22:25.360
[Guest]: Gandhi in India. There are people who detest him, who demonize him, British officials from

00:22:25.360 --> 00:22:30.240
[Guest]: the Viceroy downwards. And there's some who quite do respect and admire him. I mean, a

00:22:30.240 --> 00:22:35.920
[Guest]: little later in the story is 1922, when he's tried for sedition and comes up before Judge

00:22:35.920 --> 00:22:40.680
[Guest]: Broomfield, who says, you know, you're altogether different from any other person I've tried.

00:22:40.680 --> 00:22:44.440
[Guest]: You know, in the eyes of the law, you may be a criminal, but in the eyes of many of

00:22:44.440 --> 00:22:49.200
[Guest]: your countrymen, you're a great hero. And no one would be happier than I if your sentence

00:22:49.200 --> 00:22:56.040
[Guest]: is kind of, you know, curtailed or just, you know, reduced or withdrawn. Now, I think,

00:22:56.040 --> 00:23:00.440
[Guest]: you know, this is, of course, a theme for a separate podcast. And I mean, British state

00:23:00.440 --> 00:23:05.920
[Guest]: was also composed of human beings. You know, it was not just one abstract, unified, homogeneous

00:23:05.920 --> 00:23:11.680
[Guest]: entity out purely to do evil and oppress and brutalize the Indians. There were people there

00:23:11.680 --> 00:23:16.360
[Guest]: who empathize with Indian aspirations. There were people there who recognized the extraordinary

00:23:16.360 --> 00:23:22.320
[Guest]: person that Gandhi was. And on the other hand, there were people who were unfeeling, unreasoning,

00:23:22.320 --> 00:23:28.600
[Guest]: dismissive, arrogant, racist. And I think the variety of British reactions to Gandhi

00:23:28.600 --> 00:23:32.680
[Guest]: in India, let alone the variety of British reactions to Gandhi in Britain, which is also

00:23:32.680 --> 00:23:37.680
[Guest]: an interesting parallel story in these decades, is I think, is quite fascinating to the historian,

00:23:37.680 --> 00:23:39.720
[Amit Varma]: because there's no single British reaction to Gandhi.

00:23:39.720 --> 00:23:43.080
[Amit Varma]: And it's interesting that in the beginning, they sort of underestimate him, like you point

00:23:43.080 --> 00:23:48.080
[Amit Varma]: out how after that first speech he gave, you quote the chief secretary when they're debating

00:23:48.080 --> 00:23:51.800
[Amit Varma]: what to do about him. And he says, quote, cold water seems better than the martyr's

00:23:51.800 --> 00:23:57.080
[Amit Varma]: stake. And they sort of decide to ignore him because they don't think he'll have much impact.

00:23:57.080 --> 00:24:01.560
[Amit Varma]: And you see this play out over the next 30 years, like even the salt march, for example,

00:24:01.560 --> 00:24:05.480
[Guest]: they actually allowed him to reach Gandhi, which was again much debated at the time.

00:24:05.480 --> 00:24:10.640
[Guest]: A spectacular act of misjudgment by Irwin who thought that, you know, what is this salt

00:24:10.640 --> 00:24:15.160
[Guest]: business and what is this old man going on a march? Just ignore it. Not realizing the

00:24:15.160 --> 00:24:18.520
[Guest]: enormous symbolic significance of what Gandhi was trying to do and the way in which with

00:24:18.520 --> 00:24:23.360
[Guest]: every successive day of the march, he would capture the imagination and, and the loyalty

00:24:23.360 --> 00:24:25.160
[Amit Varma]: and affection of more and more Indians.

00:24:25.160 --> 00:24:30.680
[Amit Varma]: Now, shortly after Champaran, another sort of seminal event happens, which is that labor

00:24:30.680 --> 00:24:35.560
[Amit Varma]: dispute where he, uh, uh, you know, takes a side of some laborers against a factory

00:24:35.560 --> 00:24:39.000
[Amit Varma]: owner, Ambalal Sarabhai, who had actually donated money for his ashram and helped him

00:24:39.000 --> 00:24:44.160
[Amit Varma]: to kind of survive there. And the labor leaders are led by, um, uh, Ambalal Sarabhai's sister

00:24:44.160 --> 00:24:49.200
[Amit Varma]: Anusuya Ben and he gets together with her. And, you know, one interesting, again, you

00:24:49.200 --> 00:24:53.600
[Amit Varma]: know, speaking of contingency and luck, how things sometimes happen is that after a few

00:24:53.600 --> 00:24:57.960
[Amit Varma]: days of the agitation, the workers pointed out that, how can you empathize with us? We

00:24:57.960 --> 00:25:02.520
[Amit Varma]: are starving. You are going to your fancy house every day and eating a meal.

00:25:02.520 --> 00:25:07.200
[Amit Varma]: And then Gandhi said, okay, I will fast. Yeah. And that's how his whole tradition of fasting

00:25:07.200 --> 00:25:14.040
[Amit Varma]: begins with Gandhi as a response, as a tactical response to this criticism rather than. Yeah.

00:25:14.040 --> 00:25:19.400
[Guest]: So he had Gandhi had fasted before, but that was against the disciples in his ashram for

00:25:19.400 --> 00:25:23.520
[Guest]: violating the code of the ashram. You know, his son fell in love. One of his sons, Manilal

00:25:23.520 --> 00:25:28.680
[Guest]: fell in love in South Africa, you know, was having some kind of, uh, relationship that

00:25:28.680 --> 00:25:32.280
[Guest]: Gandhi felt was illicit and breaking the code of the ashram, Brahmacharya code of the ashram

00:25:32.280 --> 00:25:36.640
[Guest]: and he went on fast and so on. This was his first quasi social or political fast.

00:25:36.640 --> 00:25:44.240
[Guest]: And he was stung by the criticism. I think, uh, there's a, uh, Anusuya Ben who was Ambalal's

00:25:44.240 --> 00:25:50.360
[Guest]: sister, but on the other side with the workers and Gandhi to travel in a car with the splendid

00:25:50.360 --> 00:25:55.280
[Guest]: name of an overland roadster. So we had cars were very rare in the Ambala and cars really

00:25:55.280 --> 00:25:59.400
[Guest]: denoted privilege. Only the Maharajas had cars, right? So here is this so-called Fakir

00:25:59.400 --> 00:26:04.000
[Guest]: leader, the people, you know, going in a car and the worker said, Hey, what is going on?

00:26:04.000 --> 00:26:09.120
[Amit Varma]: And he was stung by that. And taking off from the, how did the spiritual persona that he

00:26:09.120 --> 00:26:13.800
[Amit Varma]: later came to adopt, like how did being called the Mahatma in terms of optics, the way he

00:26:13.800 --> 00:26:17.280
[Amit Varma]: dressed and you, you know, the simplicity with which he essentially portrayed himself

00:26:17.280 --> 00:26:22.680
[Amit Varma]: and mostly lived, um, how did that help him in becoming the sort of political superstar?

00:26:22.680 --> 00:26:27.840
[Guest]: I think very much, uh, I mean, because to go back to, uh, uh, our earlier discussion

00:26:27.840 --> 00:26:32.160
[Guest]: a few minutes ago about the Congress party, I mean, the Congress party, whether it was

00:26:32.160 --> 00:26:39.120
[Guest]: Gokhale, who was reason and moderation or Tilak, who was fired and brimstone and angry

00:26:39.120 --> 00:26:42.480
[Guest]: rhetoric, they were really divorced from the life of the ordinary people.

00:26:42.480 --> 00:26:45.680
[Guest]: I mean, Tilak had a following among the workers of Bombay, but he didn't live in the Charles.

00:26:45.680 --> 00:26:48.960
[Guest]: I mean, he still lived with middle-class people and occasionally went to the Charles to give

00:26:48.960 --> 00:26:55.080
[Guest]: a lecture. I think Gandhi's completely declassed lifestyle, you know, he declass himself totally

00:26:55.080 --> 00:26:59.680
[Guest]: in terms of his lifestyle. Again, Champaran is very important there because he lives with

00:26:59.680 --> 00:27:04.920
[Guest]: peasants, he travels with them and that kind of asceticism, the willingness to do away

00:27:04.920 --> 00:27:10.000
[Guest]: with all luxuries. And which is why when it was pointed out to him that he was traveling

00:27:10.000 --> 00:27:14.360
[Guest]: in a car, he abandoned that for the, for the, while the strike was on in Ahmedabad, but

00:27:14.360 --> 00:27:18.880
[Guest]: it marked him out from all other political leaders of the time, the other political leaders

00:27:18.880 --> 00:27:26.520
[Guest]: of the time were really elitist and disconnected from the everyday lives of peasants, workers,

00:27:26.520 --> 00:27:33.360
[Guest]: tribals, Dalits, Adivasis, you know, pastoralists, artisans, and Gandhi at least had some connection

00:27:33.360 --> 00:27:35.360
[Amit Varma]: to how those people lived.

00:27:35.360 --> 00:27:42.600
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, you also point out how Gandhi in a short span of time, uh, achieved this

00:27:42.600 --> 00:27:47.120
[Amit Varma]: mass popularity, almost like, um, you know, the way memes spread today, achieved this

00:27:47.120 --> 00:27:52.480
[Amit Varma]: mass popularity and became a huge figure in days when there was not only no internet or

00:27:52.480 --> 00:27:58.400
[Amit Varma]: social media, but no television, even like no radio, even no radio, even effectively.

00:27:58.400 --> 00:28:02.880
[Amit Varma]: So how did, how did this man just become a national figure in the span of a few months

00:28:02.880 --> 00:28:03.880
[Guest]: without all of this?

00:28:03.880 --> 00:28:06.960
[Guest]: Few years, I mean, I think more few years than few months. I think, you know, there

00:28:06.960 --> 00:28:13.080
[Guest]: was already a, a press, uh, and a burgeoning vernacular press, not just in English, but

00:28:13.080 --> 00:28:18.560
[Guest]: in different Indian languages. And it's, you know, the press was often, uh, issues of newspapers

00:28:18.560 --> 00:28:23.960
[Guest]: were often read out, you know, that, uh, under a tree in a village, you know, the one little

00:28:23.960 --> 00:28:27.520
[Guest]: person would read out the news, but it is, even then it is quite extraordinary.

00:28:27.520 --> 00:28:38.640
[Guest]: I mean, uh, I'd say by 1920, uh, Gandhi was known in every part of India, except the Northeast.

00:28:38.640 --> 00:28:43.800
[Guest]: I mean, in Assam, yes, but not in Nagaland and Meghalaya and Mizoram and Manipur, but

00:28:43.800 --> 00:28:47.960
[Guest]: except the Northeast, he was known in every part of India and he was known in every part

00:28:47.960 --> 00:28:53.360
[Guest]: of India or the impression or the perception of him in every part of India was, this is

00:28:53.360 --> 00:29:01.200
[Guest]: a man who's transparent, honest, courageous, simple, and he's here to fight for our rights.

00:29:01.200 --> 00:29:05.200
[Guest]: And that is quite extraordinary. I mean, that it essentially from 1917, which is his first

00:29:05.200 --> 00:29:12.520
[Guest]: movement in Jampal and in three years, that's how far his fame spreads. And whereas, uh,

00:29:12.520 --> 00:29:16.080
[Guest]: Tilak would have been known in the cities. Tilak would have been known in Bombay, in

00:29:16.080 --> 00:29:19.960
[Guest]: Calcutta, probably in Lahore, but not in the countryside.

00:29:19.960 --> 00:29:24.760
[Amit Varma]: And how much did it help Gandhi that in, uh, you know, during the Champaran thing, and

00:29:24.760 --> 00:29:29.480
[Amit Varma]: then during the, um, the passive resistance that took place against the Rowlatt Act, uh,

00:29:29.480 --> 00:29:32.960
[Amit Varma]: that Tilak was out of the country for some of this period. So Gandhi almost became a

00:29:32.960 --> 00:29:34.480
[Amit Varma]: de facto leader of the movement.

00:29:34.480 --> 00:29:40.000
[Guest]: Very much. Again, it goes back to just luck, pure luck. Gokhale's early death freed Gandhi

00:29:40.000 --> 00:29:44.800
[Guest]: for a life of radical action rather than, uh, you know, constraining him or confining

00:29:44.800 --> 00:29:50.000
[Guest]: him within the realm of social reform and Tilak's absence, you know, allowed Gandhi

00:29:50.000 --> 00:29:54.760
[Guest]: to become the undisputed leader of, uh, the Rowlatt Satyagraha. I mean, Tilak was the

00:29:54.760 --> 00:29:59.480
[Guest]: Rowlatt Satyagraha, which was, uh, Gandhi's first all India campaign, uh, was launched

00:29:59.480 --> 00:30:03.920
[Guest]: when Tilak was in London, fighting a court case and Tilak, who was the leader of the

00:30:03.920 --> 00:30:08.280
[Guest]: militant tendency in the Congress, as we've already discussed, would have become the default

00:30:08.280 --> 00:30:10.160
[Guest]: front of this movement.

00:30:10.160 --> 00:30:14.960
[Guest]: Gandhi not had to go to London. By the time he returns, Gandhi has already captured, you

00:30:14.960 --> 00:30:19.960
[Guest]: know, the national imagination and Tilak is generous enough to praise him. Uh, and, uh,

00:30:19.960 --> 00:30:25.560
[Guest]: a year later, Tilak himself dies and Gandhi is lucky to be in Bombay at the time of Tilak's

00:30:25.560 --> 00:30:30.360
[Guest]: funeral and he can, you know, he, uh, cremation and he can be one of the pallbearers. So there's

00:30:30.360 --> 00:30:36.200
[Guest]: a kind of symbolic transference from Tilak to Gandhi. So Tilak's absence in 1919, Tilak's

00:30:36.200 --> 00:30:41.560
[Guest]: death in 1920, uh, again, in retrospect, very fortuitous for them.

00:30:41.560 --> 00:30:46.760
[Amit Varma]: And you know, one of the sort of big moves that happens, not just for Gandhi, but for

00:30:46.760 --> 00:30:53.160
[Amit Varma]: the Congress and for India itself is what seems on the surface is almost bizarre alliance

00:30:53.160 --> 00:30:58.960
[Amit Varma]: that, um, Gandhi, um, gets into with the Ali brothers who are in the Khilafat movement.

00:30:58.960 --> 00:31:03.520
[Amit Varma]: At this point, the world war one has ended. Turkey is lost. Uh, the caliphate is gone

00:31:03.520 --> 00:31:09.040
[Amit Varma]: basically. And, um, you know, the Ali brothers and people around them are starting this Khilafat

00:31:09.040 --> 00:31:14.280
[Amit Varma]: movement demanding from the empire that they sort of bring the caliphate back. Now, through

00:31:14.280 --> 00:31:18.480
[Amit Varma]: this entire period of time, which we now forget the Muslims of India are also facing in a

00:31:18.480 --> 00:31:23.920
[Amit Varma]: sense, a crisis of dual identity that they feel that they are part of this larger calm,

00:31:23.920 --> 00:31:30.880
[Amit Varma]: this greater Muslim nation. And at the same time, there is a fight on for Indian nationhood,

00:31:30.880 --> 00:31:35.240
[Amit Varma]: you know, and, and how does this conflict sort of play out? How has it played out until

00:31:35.240 --> 00:31:41.640
[Guest]: that point? So, uh, the Khilafat is abolished during the world war and Turkey is opposing

00:31:41.640 --> 00:31:47.520
[Guest]: the allies and the Ali brothers, Mohammed and Shaukat Ali, both whom studied at Muslim

00:31:47.520 --> 00:31:53.160
[Guest]: university and charismatic orators and so on are interned in, in Chindwara, which is

00:31:53.160 --> 00:31:57.320
[Guest]: incidentally the place where Kamal Nath comes from, or where he has his pocket burrow. He

00:31:57.320 --> 00:32:03.000
[Amit Varma]: has his pocket burrow. And I didn't expect to hear that name during this episode, the

00:32:03.000 --> 00:32:07.920
[Guest]: curious, uh, uh, you know, residences that places have. So they were interned and then

00:32:07.920 --> 00:32:14.480
[Guest]: they come out of jail. Gandhi says they must be, uh, freed from house arrest and Gandhi

00:32:14.480 --> 00:32:18.360
[Guest]: is looking for a way to build bridges with ordinary Muslims, you know, not just the Muslim

00:32:18.360 --> 00:32:23.920
[Guest]: elite and here, of course, what Gandhi does, I mean, it's been subject to great debate

00:32:23.920 --> 00:32:28.960
[Guest]: and it was arguably a tactical mistake for him to bring religion. So centrally Muslim,

00:32:28.960 --> 00:32:34.480
[Guest]: the pan-Islamic, uh, loyalties of Indian Muslims. So centrally into, uh, Indian politics was

00:32:34.480 --> 00:32:38.680
[Guest]: in retrospect a mistake because, you know, it led to all kinds of problems later on.

00:32:38.680 --> 00:32:44.480
[Guest]: But I think the most, uh, plausible explanation for what Gandhi did lies in a classic essay

00:32:44.480 --> 00:32:49.080
[Guest]: written by a British scholar of India called Phillips Pratt, who had studied Gandhi's life

00:32:49.080 --> 00:32:52.400
[Guest]: very closely, who actually lived in Bangalore, married a Tamil girl and lived here. And he

00:32:52.400 --> 00:32:56.960
[Guest]: says that, look at what Gandhi was able to do in South Africa was to build bridges with

00:32:56.960 --> 00:33:02.920
[Guest]: the Muslims through personal friendship. So he befriended Kachalya, uh, he befriended,

00:33:02.920 --> 00:33:07.680
[Guest]: you know, uh, uh, Dada Abdullah. And through that, he was able to bring Muslims and Hindus

00:33:07.680 --> 00:33:13.160
[Guest]: together. I mean, he had close Muslim friends and these close Muslim friends in South Africa

00:33:13.160 --> 00:33:19.880
[Guest]: allowed him to build a kind of trans-religious community solidarity. Now, perhaps Pratt says

00:33:19.880 --> 00:33:24.200
[Guest]: that was easier in South Africa because the community was smaller. It was more cohesive.

00:33:24.200 --> 00:33:29.480
[Guest]: When in the diaspora, your religious identities are relatively less important, but in India,

00:33:29.480 --> 00:33:35.160
[Guest]: which is much larger and where the Muslims themselves are so diverse and composed of

00:33:35.160 --> 00:33:39.240
[Guest]: so many different sects, this strategy of befriending two people to bring a whole community

00:33:39.240 --> 00:33:45.480
[Guest]: on board failed. And, uh, uh, you know, it's, I think it's a very plausible kind of interpretation,

00:33:45.480 --> 00:33:51.840
[Guest]: but Gandhi felt that to bring Muslims into the fold of the freedom struggle, en masse,

00:33:51.840 --> 00:33:56.640
[Guest]: not just a few leaders, but en masse was very important that the Arya brothers could help

00:33:56.640 --> 00:34:02.080
[Guest]: him do it. And if you know, the Khilafat had a very important sentimental and symbolic

00:34:02.080 --> 00:34:07.560
[Guest]: place in the Muslim imagination, the Indian Muslim imagination. So the Hindus should support

00:34:07.560 --> 00:34:11.240
[Guest]: them in that. And in exchange, the Muslims would come on board and freedom struggle.

00:34:11.240 --> 00:34:16.160
[Guest]: They would respect Hindu sentiments, for example, on issues such as playing music before mosques

00:34:16.160 --> 00:34:20.440
[Guest]: and cow slaughter and so on and so forth. So he did it tactically and instrumentally,

00:34:20.440 --> 00:34:25.360
[Guest]: I think, and may not have been aware of the consequence. People warned him at the time.

00:34:25.360 --> 00:34:31.000
[Guest]: I mean, I quote there, uh, the warnings issued by Jadunath Sarkar, who was a right-wing historian

00:34:31.000 --> 00:34:34.400
[Guest]: and Gandhi's own friend, C.F. Andrews. He said, don't do this. They both said, don't

00:34:34.400 --> 00:34:38.520
[Amit Varma]: do this. Don't support the Khilafat movement. And it just causes great dissonance in me

00:34:38.520 --> 00:34:42.920
[Amit Varma]: when I read about it at Alliance, because on one hand it's philosophically incoherent

00:34:42.920 --> 00:34:47.560
[Amit Varma]: because Gandhi's demand is for a free India. Correct. And the Ali brothers are demanding

00:34:47.560 --> 00:34:51.200
[Amit Varma]: for a free Khilafat, which is something completely different. And India doesn't figure in that

00:34:51.200 --> 00:34:56.240
[Amit Varma]: it's, it's a wider nation out of, but on the other hand, in the proximate term, it feels

00:34:56.240 --> 00:35:00.720
[Amit Varma]: like a tactical masterstroke because getting the Muslims with him allows him to take control

00:35:00.720 --> 00:35:03.800
[Amit Varma]: of the Congress party and which is therefore changed forever.

00:35:03.800 --> 00:35:07.480
[Guest]: Absolutely. But just think of a counterfactual, I don't express it in the book. I mean, but

00:35:07.480 --> 00:35:13.400
[Guest]: you know, to give some context to it and maybe present this Alliance in a way we can understand

00:35:13.400 --> 00:35:18.400
[Guest]: why Gandhi reached out to the Ali brothers. Let's assume that in 1917, the Bolshevik revolution

00:35:18.400 --> 00:35:26.480
[Guest]: happened not in Russia, but in Italy and the Vatican and the institution of the Pope was

00:35:26.480 --> 00:35:31.440
[Guest]: abolished. All right. Now it's similar to the Khilafat in that they're Catholics in

00:35:31.440 --> 00:35:37.000
[Guest]: India, they're Catholics in Spain, the Catholics in Philippines, they're Catholics in Thailand,

00:35:37.000 --> 00:35:43.920
[Guest]: all of whom can be great and loyal and patriotic, high in Spanish and you know, Mozambican citizens,

00:35:43.920 --> 00:35:47.040
[Guest]: but yet have allegiance to the institution of the Pope, who is the head of the church

00:35:47.040 --> 00:35:52.760
[Guest]: in the Vatican in Italy. Now, what if Lenin had said, I'm in control of Italy and there's

00:35:52.760 --> 00:35:58.120
[Guest]: no Pope, I mean, the Bolsheviks were vigorously atheistic people, right? Now, what do you

00:35:58.120 --> 00:36:04.480
[Guest]: say in India to a Catholic who comes to you and say, says, if there was a Catholic community

00:36:04.480 --> 00:36:08.280
[Guest]: in India, uh, as they watch the smaller numbers come at a much smaller, but let's say they

00:36:08.280 --> 00:36:12.080
[Guest]: come to Gandhi and say, you're the leader of our freedom struggle. This is a matter

00:36:12.080 --> 00:36:16.920
[Guest]: of great sentiment and symbolic importance to us. Please agitate for the restoration

00:36:16.920 --> 00:36:21.920
[Amit Varma]: of the office of the Pope. I know what Amit Shah would say to them. He would say, come

00:36:21.920 --> 00:36:27.320
[Amit Varma]: back and become Hindu. So that's the kind of analogy you would, you know, so to make

00:36:27.320 --> 00:36:32.040
[Guest]: it more understandable and Muslim, the much larger than, uh, uh, Catholics, they were

00:36:32.040 --> 00:36:39.640
[Guest]: much more numerous, much more important. And, uh, do you say that, uh, uh, you know, uh,

00:36:39.640 --> 00:36:46.480
[Guest]: an Indian Catholic who goes to Rome is, uh, once in his or her lifetime is anti-patriotic

00:36:46.480 --> 00:36:50.520
[Guest]: or the rest of the life is spent. I mean, it's kind of a symbolic, right? Okay. Okay.

00:36:50.520 --> 00:36:55.800
[Guest]: Now come closer home. I mean, a Nepali who goes to Badrinath, right? What do you say

00:36:55.800 --> 00:37:01.840
[Guest]: to that? You know, so, or, or a Hindu in Guyana who wants to go to Badrinath, right? And is

00:37:01.840 --> 00:37:06.480
[Guest]: that Hindu in Guyana disloyal to the Guyanese state or is he an anti-national from the eyes

00:37:06.480 --> 00:37:11.360
[Guest]: of Guyana because he feels that Badrinath is a Teerthan he would like to visit. So these

00:37:11.360 --> 00:37:15.320
[Guest]: are complicated matters. And I think one should not take a black and white approach to them.

00:37:15.320 --> 00:37:18.280
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. I'm, I'm, I'm talking about sort of how it might have been seen by the British

00:37:18.280 --> 00:37:21.400
[Amit Varma]: empire or how it might have felt in terms of what they were asking for. I mean, obviously

00:37:21.400 --> 00:37:25.320
[Amit Varma]: people contain multitudes and you can be a Hindu and an Indian and a Bombayite and so

00:37:25.320 --> 00:37:30.320
[Amit Varma]: on at the same time. Uh, another thing that strikes me is at this point in time, in the

00:37:30.320 --> 00:37:33.800
[Amit Varma]: earlier years, you know, after Gandhi comes back and the two or three years after that,

00:37:33.800 --> 00:37:38.080
[Amit Varma]: he's sort of a marginal figure, like you mentioned. And at that point, Jinnah is like the next

00:37:38.080 --> 00:37:44.040
[Amit Varma]: great leader in waiting. And you know, Tilak and Annie Besant are kind of aging, the extremist

00:37:44.040 --> 00:37:48.360
[Amit Varma]: leaders. Tilak is a great moderate leader who's expecting to sort of be Gokhale's successor

00:37:48.360 --> 00:37:54.360
[Amit Varma]: and take over. And then suddenly this black swan event called Mahatma Gandhi just bursts

00:37:54.360 --> 00:37:59.160
[Amit Varma]: into the scene and knocks him off the perch. And suddenly he's, he's kind of marginalized

00:37:59.160 --> 00:38:04.800
[Amit Varma]: and does that personal hurt and his change in direction after that point change history

00:38:04.800 --> 00:38:05.800
[Amit Varma]: substantially?

00:38:05.800 --> 00:38:11.480
[Guest]: Yes, I think, I think it does. And it, it predates it. I mean, I, I go back, I mean,

00:38:11.480 --> 00:38:16.280
[Guest]: most historians would talk about, of course, Gandhi's leadership of the rural Satyagraha,

00:38:16.280 --> 00:38:20.520
[Guest]: which established him as an all India figure. And then the next year, the non-cooperation

00:38:20.520 --> 00:38:26.720
[Guest]: movement and the meeting in Nagpur where Jinnah is shouted down by the mob of Gandhi Bhakts.

00:38:26.720 --> 00:38:30.240
[Guest]: I mean, they were really Gandhi Bhakts, you know, who are then running the Communist Party.

00:38:30.240 --> 00:38:34.400
[Guest]: But I would predate this to 1915. I mean, I'd, I'd say early in, in an early chapter

00:38:34.400 --> 00:38:39.000
[Guest]: that when Gandhi comes back and there's a reception to Gandhi in Bombay by the Gujarati

00:38:39.000 --> 00:38:43.960
[Guest]: community of Bombay and K. M. Munshi, later to be the founder of the Bharatiya Vidya Bhavan,

00:38:43.960 --> 00:38:48.200
[Guest]: but at that time a rising lawyer and scholar, welcomes Gandhi and says, you're the greatest

00:38:48.200 --> 00:38:52.800
[Guest]: person ever from Gujarat. And Jinnah must have been really stung by this because Jinnah

00:38:52.800 --> 00:38:57.880
[Guest]: was a Gujarati who was in conventional terms, had a far more successful political career

00:38:57.880 --> 00:39:01.440
[Guest]: than Gandhi. I mean, he was already a member of the Imperial Council. He was a great success

00:39:01.440 --> 00:39:05.720
[Guest]: in the Bombay Bar, which Gandhi had conspicuously failed to be and so on. So I think there is

00:39:05.720 --> 00:39:13.520
[Guest]: that element of personal rivalry at being overshadowed, overtaken, sidelined, marginalized

00:39:13.520 --> 00:39:19.040
[Guest]: by a person who's a Johnny come lately and whom Jinnah clearly sees in professional terms

00:39:19.040 --> 00:39:20.040
[Guest]: as inferior.

00:39:20.040 --> 00:39:24.600
[Amit Varma]: And in an aside, in both your books, you mentioned that they could have been business partners.

00:39:24.600 --> 00:39:28.920
[Guest]: Yes, yes. In 1897, they could have been business partners in South Africa. Absolutely. I mean,

00:39:28.920 --> 00:39:33.480
[Guest]: they always had a partnership because, you know, Gandhi was in South Africa. We have

00:39:33.480 --> 00:39:38.640
[Guest]: discussed this in the first episode. He was the only Indian lawyer. He wanted a partner

00:39:38.640 --> 00:39:42.560
[Guest]: since a large proportion of the diasporic community in South Africa was Muslim. It made

00:39:42.560 --> 00:39:47.360
[Guest]: sense to have a Muslim partner. And there is some very strong speculative evidence to

00:39:47.360 --> 00:39:51.000
[Guest]: suggest that he had approached Jinnah to join him in a partnership.

00:39:51.000 --> 00:39:54.120
[Amit Varma]: That would have been a fun counterfactual. We'll take a quick commercial break and then

