[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the Scene and the Unseen. I'm chatting with Ram Goa about Mahatma Gandhi's

00:41:42.600 --> 00:41:49.040
[Amit Varma]: years in India. And for a moment, I want to take a break from the chronology of what he

00:41:49.040 --> 00:41:55.640
[Amit Varma]: did and how he rose to greatness and tackle one of the big themes in the book and in Gandhi's

00:41:55.640 --> 00:42:01.240
[Amit Varma]: journey and all of India, in fact, which is caste. And it's really interesting because

00:42:01.240 --> 00:42:06.620
[Amit Varma]: through the years you see Gandhi sort of trying to come to terms with it. And I'm not convinced

00:42:06.620 --> 00:42:10.880
[Amit Varma]: he ever did. And there are these different sort of contradictory quotes, which like,

00:42:10.880 --> 00:42:16.520
[Amit Varma]: you know, there is one quote, which he gives in Mayavaran quote, if it was proof to me

00:42:16.520 --> 00:42:22.120
[Amit Varma]: that caste is an essential part of Hinduism, I for one would declare myself an open rebel

00:42:22.120 --> 00:42:26.400
[Amit Varma]: against Hinduism itself. Stop quote, which seems like a strong stand, but there's an

00:42:26.400 --> 00:42:31.960
[Amit Varma]: if at the start of it. And Gandhi sort of had this, it almost seemed to me that he was

00:42:31.960 --> 00:42:38.640
[Amit Varma]: in denial of how pervasive caste was that, you know, while, you know, Ambedkar later

00:42:38.640 --> 00:42:43.960
[Amit Varma]: on would talk about the annihilation of caste and that it was hard coded into Hinduism itself.

00:42:43.960 --> 00:42:48.680
[Amit Varma]: Gandhi sort of seemed to believe in something called Varna Ashram Dharma, which he cited

00:42:48.680 --> 00:42:53.160
[Amit Varma]: when there was talk of an untouchable family entering his ashram. And he said that according

00:42:53.160 --> 00:42:57.120
[Amit Varma]: to Varna Ashram Dharma, which he held to be valid, people of different castes can't stay

00:42:57.120 --> 00:43:01.160
[Amit Varma]: under the same roof and eat at the same table. And he said, I'll make an exception for my

00:43:01.160 --> 00:43:05.360
[Amit Varma]: ashram because we are not functioning under the same rules, but I'm not going to ask other

00:43:05.360 --> 00:43:10.680
[Amit Varma]: people to sort of follow these rules. And he had a view where like the four, he once

00:43:10.680 --> 00:43:15.440
[Amit Varma]: said, quote, he wanted to improve the caste system rather than uproot it. And his view

00:43:15.440 --> 00:43:19.480
[Amit Varma]: seemed to be that the caste system isn't bad per se, untouchability is bad, but the four

00:43:19.480 --> 00:43:24.160
[Guest]: varnas can exist. Yeah, that's the position he starts with. And I think it's important

00:43:24.160 --> 00:43:29.560
[Guest]: to recognize that Gandhi's feeling is way around India. I mean, he's, you know, he's

00:43:29.560 --> 00:43:35.320
[Guest]: an outsider. He has to establish his authority of the political movement. He has to prove

00:43:35.320 --> 00:43:42.480
[Guest]: his credentials as a social reformer. Caste is, you know, caste divisions, boundaries

00:43:42.480 --> 00:43:48.680
[Guest]: are very pervasive in Hindu society. He is someone who does not know Sanskrit. He is

00:43:48.680 --> 00:43:53.280
[Guest]: not a Brahmin. So there'll be questions about how he interprets tradition. And he started

00:43:53.280 --> 00:43:57.680
[Guest]: to do several things at the same time. I mean, he's leading a movement for political freedom.

00:43:57.680 --> 00:44:05.200
[Guest]: He is forging a compact with Hindus and Muslims, and he's trying to abolish untouchability.

00:44:05.200 --> 00:44:10.680
[Guest]: And clearly he, if he has to move on all fronts, he has to move slowly. And I think the depth

00:44:10.680 --> 00:44:17.000
[Guest]: of hostility to even his limited attempts to attack untouchability early on, from the

00:44:17.000 --> 00:44:22.360
[Guest]: time in 1915, when he admits a Dalit family and his funding collapses, right, and is even

00:44:22.360 --> 00:44:26.760
[Guest]: a possibility the whole of upper caste society in Ahmedabad ostracize him, to later on through

00:44:26.760 --> 00:44:31.400
[Guest]: the twenties and thirties, when the most vicious and vehement attacks on him are not from Dalit

00:44:31.400 --> 00:44:36.840
[Guest]: radicals, but from upper caste orthodox people, including attempts on his life. So I think

00:44:36.840 --> 00:44:41.760
[Guest]: it's in that context that one has to understand why he moves slowly. You know, so among the

00:44:41.760 --> 00:44:46.400
[Guest]: people who radicalize him, well before Ambedkar, is a man called T.K. Madhavan, who is a follower

00:44:46.400 --> 00:44:51.960
[Guest]: of the great Malayali social reformer, Narayan Guru, who visits Gandhi in Tirunelveli in

00:44:51.960 --> 00:44:55.760
[Guest]: 1921, when Gandhi is doing non-cooperation work. And he comes up from Kerala and says,

00:44:55.760 --> 00:45:00.320
[Guest]: you know, you're against untouchability, that's good, but why can't Dalits enter temples?

00:45:00.320 --> 00:45:04.040
[Guest]: And Gandhi says, no, no, no, I'm not sure, you know, at the moment, you know, that may

00:45:04.040 --> 00:45:08.320
[Guest]: not be such a good idea. But in three or four years, he changes his mind and he blesses

00:45:08.320 --> 00:45:14.120
[Guest]: the Vaikam Satyagraha, which is the start of the struggle to make Dalits equal in the

00:45:14.120 --> 00:45:18.680
[Guest]: eyes of God. And if Dalits and upper caste Hindus are rubbing bodies, going together

00:45:18.680 --> 00:45:23.960
[Guest]: for the temple, that is a major blow against untouchability. But Gandhi is moved along

00:45:23.960 --> 00:45:29.800
[Guest]: that path by people more radical than him, to begin with Narayan Guru and his followers

00:45:29.800 --> 00:45:36.360
[Guest]: and later on Ambedkar, of course. And of course, from advocating temple entry, he then advocates

00:45:36.360 --> 00:45:41.020
[Guest]: later on intermarriage from the early 30s, when his own son, his youngest son marries

00:45:41.020 --> 00:45:46.240
[Guest]: outside the caste and then further down the decade where he solemnized a series of marriages

00:45:46.240 --> 00:45:51.240
[Guest]: between Dalits and non-Dalits. And once you advocate intermarriage, you've effectively

00:45:51.240 --> 00:45:55.800
[Guest]: undermined the whole caste system. So I think the evolution of Gandhi's views is very important

00:45:55.800 --> 00:46:02.040
[Guest]: that he's moving in a more egalitarian, more progressive, more radical direction. And one

00:46:02.040 --> 00:46:06.240
[Guest]: must not cherry pick him, pick quotes from an earlier period of life and claim that he

00:46:06.240 --> 00:46:08.200
[Amit Varma]: stood by those views all through.

00:46:08.200 --> 00:46:13.200
[Amit Varma]: And is it sort of complicated to look at the utterances of a public intellectual who's

00:46:13.200 --> 00:46:18.080
[Amit Varma]: also a politician? Because a public intellectual's imperatives are just to be true to his thoughts.

00:46:18.080 --> 00:46:24.320
[Guest]: Absolutely. Absolutely. You're quite right. He was trying to move society in certain ways.

00:46:24.320 --> 00:46:28.800
[Amit Varma]: Can a lot of his utterances also be a sort of hedging that while he's saying that yes,

00:46:28.800 --> 00:46:32.240
[Amit Varma]: caste is bad, he at the same time doesn't want to piss off the orthodoxy too much. So

00:46:32.240 --> 00:46:33.800
[Guest]: he hedges by saying that no.

00:46:33.800 --> 00:46:37.840
[Guest]: Because he wants to build a broad-based coalition against the British at the same time. I mean,

00:46:37.840 --> 00:46:41.600
[Guest]: in the old days, the Marxists attacked him for not advocating revolutionary violence

00:46:41.600 --> 00:46:45.960
[Guest]: against Zamendars and expropriation of property. That's because he wanted Zamendars and landless

00:46:45.960 --> 00:46:49.800
[Guest]: laborers both to be in the struggle for freedom. And he would have wanted, of course, a more

00:46:49.800 --> 00:46:56.000
[Guest]: equal distribution of land that could come in time and through more gradualist methods.

00:46:56.000 --> 00:47:00.280
[Guest]: Now there remains a major difference between him and Ambedkar, which you pointed to in

00:47:00.280 --> 00:47:06.320
[Guest]: your initial remarks and questions, Amit, which is that it's a major philosophical difference.

00:47:06.320 --> 00:47:11.800
[Guest]: Ambedkar thought that untouchability and caste distinctions were integral to Hinduism. And

00:47:11.800 --> 00:47:18.720
[Guest]: hence the Dalits had to move away. In 1935, he says, I was born a Hindu, but I will not

00:47:18.720 --> 00:47:23.760
[Guest]: die a Hindu. Ambedkar says this. He considers Islam, he considers Christianity, he considers

00:47:23.760 --> 00:47:29.960
[Guest]: Sikhism and very late in life in 1956, long after Gandhi is dead, he embraces Buddhism,

00:47:29.960 --> 00:47:32.040
[Guest]: but tragically dies six weeks later.

00:47:32.040 --> 00:47:39.560
[Guest]: Now, so Ambedkar's position from 1935 was Hinduism is incapable of root and branch reform.

00:47:39.560 --> 00:47:44.080
[Guest]: It can do cosmetic reform, but not root and branch reform. Whereas Gandhi thought, I can

00:47:44.080 --> 00:47:49.360
[Guest]: save Hinduism by abolishing untouchability. So in that sense, Gandhi both lived and died

00:47:49.360 --> 00:47:54.120
[Guest]: a Hindu, whereas Ambedkar felt that for his people, they had to escape the Hindu fold.

00:47:54.120 --> 00:47:59.160
[Guest]: And that is the other philosophical differences between the two, which are in some ways equally

00:47:59.160 --> 00:48:05.840
[Guest]: important. One is that Ambedkar came from a modernist, statist, quasi-socialist tradition

00:48:05.840 --> 00:48:11.320
[Guest]: and felt the state is the agency of reform. You need laws, you need policies. And Gandhi

00:48:11.320 --> 00:48:16.240
[Guest]: felt that social reform comes from within, from individuals reforming themselves, from

00:48:16.240 --> 00:48:21.160
[Guest]: collective community action. That is the difference that can be reconciled between Gandhi and

00:48:21.160 --> 00:48:25.560
[Guest]: Ambedkar. Because clearly, if you want to end caste discrimination totally, you need

00:48:25.560 --> 00:48:28.420
[Guest]: both community renewal and purposive state action.

00:48:28.420 --> 00:48:34.920
[Guest]: But the first philosophical difference, which is that can Dalits live a life of absolute

00:48:34.920 --> 00:48:39.360
[Guest]: equality and self-respect within the Hindu fold, or do they have to go somewhere else?

00:48:39.360 --> 00:48:44.200
[Guest]: It's still an open question. I mean, one can't really answer that definitively, either on

00:48:44.200 --> 00:48:45.600
[Amit Varma]: the side of Gandhi or Ambedkar.

00:48:45.600 --> 00:48:49.440
[Amit Varma]: In fact, there's an excellent quote I picked up from your book where Ambedkar says, quote,

00:48:49.440 --> 00:48:54.240
[Amit Varma]: the outcast is a by-product of the caste system. There will be outcasts as long as there is

00:48:54.240 --> 00:48:55.240
[Amit Varma]: caste. Yes, yes, yes.

00:48:55.240 --> 00:49:00.520
[Amit Varma]: And of course, caste is inextricably tied to Hinduism in his notion. And Gandhi sort

00:49:00.520 --> 00:49:04.960
[Amit Varma]: of had this approach that, listen, you know, don't worry about it. It's, you know, the

00:49:04.960 --> 00:49:08.240
[Amit Varma]: upper caste will reform through, you know, you appeal to their conscience and they will

00:49:08.240 --> 00:49:12.960
[Amit Varma]: reform on their own. And there almost seems something condescending sometimes about his

00:49:12.960 --> 00:49:18.840
[Amit Varma]: approach to Ambedkar. Like at one point, you quote him much later on referring to praising

00:49:18.840 --> 00:49:24.480
[Amit Varma]: Ambedkar as quote, intellectually superior to thousands of intelligent and educated caste

00:49:24.480 --> 00:49:30.560
[Amit Varma]: Hindus, stop quote. And this is outrageously condescending. Yeah, absolutely. Absolutely.

00:49:30.560 --> 00:49:35.040
[Guest]: He could be condescending towards the community too, more generally. For example, when Ambedkar

00:49:35.040 --> 00:49:38.880
[Guest]: says, why doesn't the Harijan Sevak Sangh have Harijan? He says, no, it's the upper caste

00:49:38.880 --> 00:49:42.800
[Guest]: Hindus who have to repent. You know, but I think if the Harijan Sevak Sangh had had upper

00:49:42.800 --> 00:49:46.960
[Guest]: caste and Dalits together, and together they would have presented a joint front, I think

00:49:46.960 --> 00:49:50.360
[Guest]: that like the Khilafat movement, that would have been more effective. So they are clearly,

00:49:50.360 --> 00:49:57.280
[Guest]: you know, decisions he takes, statements he makes that are patronizing. But having said

00:49:57.280 --> 00:50:03.520
[Guest]: that, I think it must be put on record that Gandhi did more than any other upper caste

00:50:03.520 --> 00:50:09.880
[Guest]: Hindu in the history of modern India to delegitimize untouchability. I mean, he frequently abandoned

00:50:09.880 --> 00:50:15.000
[Guest]: his political career to launch, you know, to go on a march against untouchability. He

00:50:15.000 --> 00:50:19.800
[Guest]: risked his own, you know, status and career by taking on this question. He, as I said,

00:50:19.800 --> 00:50:25.080
[Guest]: there were attempts on his life from 1915 onwards, he's preaching the abolition of untouchability.

00:50:25.080 --> 00:50:29.640
[Guest]: So you could say he did more, he did more than anyone else in his position. I mean,

00:50:29.640 --> 00:50:38.720
[Guest]: so Patel, Nehru, Bose, Madan Moliya Amalya, Dange, Nambudripad, Srinivas Shastri, all

00:50:38.720 --> 00:50:42.440
[Guest]: the other Hindu leaders of the time, whether in the Congress, to the left of the Congress,

00:50:42.440 --> 00:50:46.680
[Guest]: right of Lohia, Jayaprakash, none of them talked about untouchability or attacked it

00:50:46.680 --> 00:50:51.400
[Guest]: so seriously and systematically as Gandhi. The only leader in the Congress party from

00:50:51.400 --> 00:50:57.480
[Guest]: 1915 to 1948 in Gandhi's death, the only major leader in the Congress party who understood

00:50:57.480 --> 00:51:01.520
[Guest]: the significance of Gandhi's campaign was Raja Gopalachari, no one else.

00:51:01.520 --> 00:51:05.880
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, it's telling that not only did he, um, uh, let in those, uh, the, the Dalit

00:51:05.880 --> 00:51:09.440
[Amit Varma]: families who wanted to be in his ashram, but visitors to his ashram, as you've cited in

00:51:09.440 --> 00:51:13.160
[Amit Varma]: your book, describe him eating out of the same plate, like someone had half a fruit

00:51:13.160 --> 00:51:18.840
[Amit Varma]: and then shared it with Gandhi. And he, and I'll just talk about this. Right, right, right.

00:51:18.840 --> 00:51:23.880
[Amit Varma]: And what also happens later on is that, uh, he starts this magazine called Harijan and

00:51:23.880 --> 00:51:28.560
[Amit Varma]: he starts a society called Harijan Sevak Sangh. And both of these seem, it seemed to me as

00:51:28.560 --> 00:51:33.800
[Amit Varma]: I was following the chronology in the book happened sort of after or in the middle of

00:51:33.800 --> 00:51:40.000
[Amit Varma]: his heated debates. And it almost seemed in one sense that he's like, you know, I have

00:51:40.000 --> 00:51:44.520
[Amit Varma]: been fighting for caste for so many years and now I am being challenged in this way

00:51:44.520 --> 00:51:49.720
[Amit Varma]: and I will show my loyalty to the cause and I will call my, um, uh, magazine Harijan.

00:51:49.720 --> 00:51:53.920
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, and, and Rajaji saw this, that there was also a touch of condescension

00:51:53.920 --> 00:51:56.560
[Guest]: and is calling the organization Harijan Sevak Sangh.

00:51:56.560 --> 00:52:01.480
[Guest]: Yeah. And Rajaji says, call it anti untouchability league or untouchability abolition league,

00:52:01.480 --> 00:52:06.880
[Guest]: because the idea is to abolish untouchability. And there's a bureaucratic, uh, you know,

00:52:06.880 --> 00:52:11.400
[Guest]: objection saying we already printed the stationery, you know, is what, so we can't change the

00:52:11.400 --> 00:52:16.840
[Guest]: name now. But in retrospect, Rajaji was absolutely farsighted on this because the name Harijan

00:52:16.840 --> 00:52:21.400
[Guest]: has a condescending ring to it and has been rightly rejected and repudiated by Dalits

00:52:21.400 --> 00:52:27.280
[Amit Varma]: today. And, uh, you know, Ambedkar's battles against, um, you know, Gandhi were always

00:52:27.280 --> 00:52:32.320
[Amit Varma]: sort of civil, but very heated and strident. Like, uh, he spoke about how Gandhi wants

00:52:32.320 --> 00:52:36.880
[Amit Varma]: to play a double role, uh, quote unquote data for Mahatma and a politician. And he wrote

00:52:36.880 --> 00:52:42.040
[Amit Varma]: this book in July, 1945, what Congress and Gandhi have done to the untouchables, which

00:52:42.040 --> 00:52:47.000
[Amit Varma]: was a scathing diatribe. It disturbed Gandhi. He asked Rajaji to write a rejoinder to it,

00:52:47.000 --> 00:52:51.920
[Amit Varma]: which Rajaji eventually did. And you know, Ambedkar in a sense also, therefore through

00:52:51.920 --> 00:52:56.440
[Amit Varma]: doubts on the whole independence project where he said that Dalits in India, untouchables

00:52:56.440 --> 00:53:00.600
[Amit Varma]: in India have the same status as Negroes in the U S how will independence help us?

00:53:00.600 --> 00:53:05.560
[Guest]: Yeah, absolutely. And I think, but I think together, I mean, even as a historian, uh,

00:53:05.560 --> 00:53:09.840
[Guest]: you know, uh, you, uh, look at it in context and you depict their battles and their struggles

00:53:09.840 --> 00:53:15.360
[Guest]: and the arguments and the, but in retrospect, I think India needed both Gandhi and Ambedkar.

00:53:15.360 --> 00:53:19.200
[Guest]: It needed, you know, a radical reform from below and a guilt-ridden, you know, upper

00:53:19.200 --> 00:53:23.400
[Guest]: caste reformer from above, uh, to together delegitimize the caste system. And the real

00:53:23.400 --> 00:53:26.760
[Guest]: tragedy, I mean, this is, this is something beyond the scope of my book, which ends with

00:53:26.760 --> 00:53:32.360
[Guest]: it. The real tragedy of the struggle against caste discrimination is that after Gandhi's

00:53:32.360 --> 00:53:37.680
[Guest]: death, the Gandhians abandoned it. Someone like Vinoba Bhave never took it up. You know,

00:53:37.680 --> 00:53:41.720
[Guest]: it had to be an ongoing struggle. It had to be taken up by upper caste social reformers

00:53:41.720 --> 00:53:47.720
[Guest]: in a completely selfless and systematic way. And they really didn't do it. So they abandoned

00:53:47.720 --> 00:53:51.560
[Guest]: Gandhi. I mean, the Gandhians abandoned Gandhi in this respect after 1948.

00:53:51.560 --> 00:53:56.080
[Amit Varma]: And even during the struggle, what was the attitude of the other office fellow leaders,

00:53:56.080 --> 00:54:00.440
[Guest]: so to say like Nehru, Patel? They were not really very, they thought that it was a deviation

00:54:00.440 --> 00:54:04.240
[Amit Varma]: from the struggle for political freedom. That's essentially how they saw it. And how do you

00:54:04.240 --> 00:54:09.240
[Guest]: personally, how do you view Ambedkar? I mean, I view him as an extraordinary figure, a person

00:54:09.240 --> 00:54:12.920
[Guest]: of great courage. I'm going to take on the Mahatma who was that much older than him,

00:54:12.920 --> 00:54:19.080
[Guest]: a brilliant scholar, but at the same time, a polemicist, someone who maybe found it hard

00:54:19.080 --> 00:54:24.520
[Guest]: to get along with people because he was, you know, uh, a person who was so brilliant. Uh,

00:54:24.520 --> 00:54:31.520
[Guest]: you know, he essentially did not have, uh, he had, uh, people who he disagreed with and

00:54:31.520 --> 00:54:37.280
[Guest]: people who followed him. You know, he does not seem to have had, I mean, there's some

00:54:37.280 --> 00:54:41.840
[Guest]: indications that he may have had an emotional relationship with an English woman to whom

00:54:41.840 --> 00:54:45.520
[Guest]: he dedicates one of his books, but that's not being fleshed out. And later on, he had

00:54:45.520 --> 00:54:51.080
[Guest]: some kind of companionship with his second wife. Uh, but he was, maybe it's, he was lonely

00:54:51.080 --> 00:54:55.440
[Guest]: because that's how, uh, he still trusts him in that role. He still trusts him in the role

00:54:55.440 --> 00:55:01.040
[Guest]: of someone who was too independent minded to loyally follow Gandhi. And because he was

00:55:01.040 --> 00:55:06.360
[Guest]: too independent minded to loyally follow Gandhi, he had to make common cause with the British,

00:55:06.360 --> 00:55:10.160
[Guest]: which alienated him from his fellow Indians. So he's an extraordinary figure, but it's

00:55:10.160 --> 00:55:18.000
[Guest]: the element of both great heroism and some tragedy in, you know, in his life. You know,

00:55:18.000 --> 00:55:22.880
[Guest]: I obviously, you know, it's, uh, admire both people enormously. I mean, and one of the

00:55:22.880 --> 00:55:27.640
[Guest]: interesting aspects of my book, I mean, now that I look back on it is that Ambedkar is

00:55:27.640 --> 00:55:33.840
[Guest]: much more important than Jinnah. You know, so if you look at, compare my biography, Amit,

00:55:33.840 --> 00:55:39.200
[Guest]: with biographies of Gandhi written 15, 10 years ago, 20 years ago, 30 years ago, 40

00:55:39.200 --> 00:55:43.520
[Guest]: years ago, 50 years ago, you will find in those older biographies, Jinnah looms much

00:55:43.520 --> 00:55:47.680
[Guest]: larger than Ambedkar. That's right. Okay. And I realized this only when I finished the

00:55:47.680 --> 00:55:51.640
[Guest]: book, you know, and Jinnah is there, Jinnah is an important figure. Ambedkar is much more

00:55:51.640 --> 00:55:57.040
[Guest]: important because Jinnah was merely posing a political challenge to Gandhi, whereas Ambedkar

00:55:57.040 --> 00:56:02.400
[Guest]: was posing a political and a moral challenge to Gandhi. And the debate between Gandhi and

00:56:02.400 --> 00:56:07.480
[Guest]: Jinnah ended in 1947 because Pakistan was created. The debate between Gandhi and Ambedkar

00:56:07.480 --> 00:56:11.680
[Guest]: continues so long as there's caste discrimination, that debate continues. So it just strikes

00:56:11.680 --> 00:56:16.960
[Guest]: me. I mean, someone should do a kind of analysis of my biography versus previous biographies,

00:56:16.960 --> 00:56:21.400
[Guest]: purely in terms of the number of index entries that Ambedkar and Jinnah have here. I mean,

00:56:21.400 --> 00:56:25.480
[Guest]: most notoriously Attenborough wrote Ambedkar out of his film totally. Ambedkar doesn't

00:56:25.480 --> 00:56:29.440
[Guest]: think, okay, and Jinnah is the fall guy, the kind of the villain. But I'm sure if you look

00:56:29.440 --> 00:56:34.960
[Guest]: at Walpert's book on Gandhi or Rajmohan Gandhi's book on Gandhi or Judith Brown's book on Gandhi

00:56:34.960 --> 00:56:38.960
[Guest]: or B. R. Nanda's book on Gandhi, all very good books. So Jeffrey Ashe's book on Gandhi,

00:56:38.960 --> 00:56:42.680
[Guest]: Louis Fisher's book on Gandhi. I have a photo of Louis Fisher and Ambedkar in my book, you

00:56:42.680 --> 00:56:47.240
[Guest]: know, so they knew each other, but I suspect Louis Fisher's book, sometimes I read it,

00:56:47.240 --> 00:56:52.320
[Guest]: you know, Jinnah will be much more important than Ambedkar in the narrative. So I think

00:56:52.320 --> 00:57:00.880
[Guest]: he was Gandhi's greatest, most insightful, most persistent, and most courageous critic.

00:57:00.880 --> 00:57:04.240
[Guest]: That's what Ambedkar was in Gandhi's life. He was many other things besides. I mean,

00:57:04.240 --> 00:57:08.520
[Guest]: he was a constitutionalist, a scholar and economist, but in Gandhi's life, I think he

00:57:08.520 --> 00:57:14.680
[Amit Varma]: was his, he was Gandhi's most important interlocutor. And like Gandhi, he actually contained multitudes

00:57:14.680 --> 00:57:18.760
[Amit Varma]: in terms of he wrote so much and he changed his mind so often that it's very hard to sort

00:57:18.760 --> 00:57:22.560
[Amit Varma]: of get a grip of the man. And I haven't read much Ambedkar. So I'll throw to you a question

00:57:22.560 --> 00:57:25.920
[Amit Varma]: a friend asked me recently, and I don't have an answer to it, which is if one wants to

00:57:25.920 --> 00:57:30.080
[Amit Varma]: discover Ambedkar's thought, what is the best place to start? What are the best books? On

00:57:30.080 --> 00:57:36.760
[Guest]: him or by him? You see, the best place to start is Byron Rodrigues, who's a very fine

00:57:36.760 --> 00:57:42.000
[Guest]: scholar political theorist from Mangalore, did a book called The Essential Writings

00:57:42.000 --> 00:57:49.080
[Guest]: of B. R. Ambedkar, which he edited, and which has a 50 page introduction, and which is a

00:57:49.080 --> 00:57:53.000
[Guest]: selection of Ambedkar's writings. That is one book I would recommend. The other book

00:57:53.000 --> 00:57:58.400
[Guest]: I would recommend is by the late D. R. Nagaraj, who was again, I'm sorry to recommend two

00:57:58.400 --> 00:58:02.880
[Guest]: books by residents of Karnataka, fellow citizens of Karnataka, but that's how they're both

00:58:02.880 --> 00:58:08.600
[Guest]: first-rate books. D. R. Nagaraj was a brilliant intellectual, Kannada, bilingual Kannada English

00:58:08.600 --> 00:58:13.080
[Guest]: intellectual who died tragically young. And he wrote a book called The Flaming Feet, which

00:58:13.080 --> 00:58:18.720
[Guest]: first appeared in 1993. And his student Prithvi Dutta Chandra Shobhi has revised and expanded

00:58:18.720 --> 00:58:23.000
[Guest]: it in a new edition with Permanent Black published, which is an account of the Dalit movement

00:58:23.000 --> 00:58:28.960
[Guest]: in Karnataka and Ambedkar's place in it. I'd say those are two very important books. There's

00:58:28.960 --> 00:58:34.560
[Guest]: a lot of hagiographic, worshipful writing on Ambedkar, including by scholars, which

00:58:34.560 --> 00:58:40.560
[Guest]: I don't take very seriously. There's a reasonably good book by Eleanor Zelliot published 50

00:58:40.560 --> 00:58:46.080
[Guest]: years ago, or the Bahar movement per se, which Ambedkar led. Dhananjay Kheer's biography

00:58:46.080 --> 00:58:52.560
[Guest]: of Ambedkar is unequalled for factual information, but very badly written and put together. And

00:58:52.560 --> 00:58:57.000
[Guest]: the world awaits a good critical biography of Ambedkar. I think he's a figure who has

00:58:57.000 --> 00:59:03.280
[Guest]: just not been written about with the kind of analytical robustness that he deserves.

00:59:03.280 --> 00:59:06.840
[Amit Varma]: I know you must be exhausted after these Gandhi books, but is that something you'd ever do?

00:59:06.840 --> 00:59:12.480
[Guest]: It has been suggested to me, Amit, but I won't do it for a few years, if at all. I mean,

00:59:12.480 --> 00:59:19.120
[Guest]: some younger scholars should do it. Again, there's room for many books on Ambedkar. There's

00:59:19.120 --> 00:59:22.400
[Guest]: some writings on Marathi. I don't read Marathi, so I don't know how good they are. You need

00:59:22.400 --> 00:59:27.800
[Guest]: a really good, proper biography. And then you need several good thematic books on him,

00:59:27.800 --> 00:59:32.680
[Guest]: you know, which take up his constitutional thinking and so on and so forth. And like

00:59:32.680 --> 00:59:36.840
[Guest]: was the Rajaji, you know, Rajaji is another great figure whom the last good book, Vasanthi

00:59:36.840 --> 00:59:41.560
[Guest]: Srinivasan wrote a short book on his political thought, but he again awaits rediscovery.

00:59:41.560 --> 00:59:45.600
[Guest]: There's too much written on Gandhi and Patel and Nehru and not enough on people like Rajaji

00:59:45.600 --> 00:59:48.000
[Amit Varma]: and Ambedkar, of quality.

00:59:48.000 --> 00:59:55.200
[Amit Varma]: So getting back to the subject of our episode, which is Gandhi, another sort of area he had,

00:59:55.200 --> 00:59:59.400
[Amit Varma]: you know, where one can have conflicting views about what Gandhi thought about it and how

00:59:59.400 --> 01:00:05.320
[Amit Varma]: he acted is women. And, you know, early on in your book, you quote him as saying that

01:00:05.320 --> 01:00:11.640
[Amit Varma]: in a nation where sort of women are not part of active political and social life, quote,

01:00:11.640 --> 01:00:16.720
[Amit Varma]: the nation walks on one leg only, stop quote, which is a very eloquent way of putting it.

01:00:16.720 --> 01:00:21.280
[Amit Varma]: But his view of women was always sort of very paternalistic, not just, not just in the way

01:00:21.280 --> 01:00:26.280
[Amit Varma]: he treated Kasurba and his own family in that Hindu patriarch way as he described, but he

01:00:26.280 --> 01:00:31.760
[Amit Varma]: was just paternalistic, like much later when he's responding to a letter by a correspondent

01:00:31.760 --> 01:00:37.840
[Amit Varma]: who's written to him, he writes about his, his view of the modern girl. And that goes,

01:00:37.840 --> 01:00:42.320
[Amit Varma]: quote, I have a fear that the modern girl loves to be Juliet to half a dozen Romeos.

01:00:42.320 --> 01:00:47.040
[Amit Varma]: She loves adventure. My correspondent seems to represent the unusual type. The modern

01:00:47.040 --> 01:00:52.400
[Amit Varma]: girl dresses not to protect herself from wind, rain or sun, but to attract attention. She

01:00:52.400 --> 01:00:58.520
[Amit Varma]: improves upon nature by painting herself and looking extraordinary, stop quote. And obviously

01:00:58.520 --> 01:01:03.600
[Amit Varma]: this, this got a heated response from the young ladies who, you know, nice feminist

01:01:03.600 --> 01:01:08.200
[Amit Varma]: response. And then he kind of responded to this with, you know, what, what reminded me

01:01:08.200 --> 01:01:11.560
[Amit Varma]: recently of another name I didn't think I would take in this episode of Rani Mukherjee,

01:01:11.560 --> 01:01:16.760
[Amit Varma]: where he seems to do a bit of victim blaming later, where he says, stop quote, the girls

01:01:16.760 --> 01:01:22.920
[Amit Varma]: must learn the art of protecting themselves against the ruffianly behavior of man, stop

01:01:22.920 --> 01:01:27.440
[Amit Varma]: quote. So he's, you know, while he does pay lip service to women being equal to men and

01:01:27.440 --> 01:01:30.400
[Amit Varma]: being an equal part of the nation, it's this kind of very paternalistic.

01:01:30.400 --> 01:01:36.000
[Guest]: So, you know, one of the episodes that you described, you know, this is one of the highlights

01:01:36.000 --> 01:01:42.680
[Guest]: of doing archival research. So Gandhi writes on women, where he says that, you know, they're

01:01:42.680 --> 01:01:46.560
[Guest]: looking for, that Julia's looking for Romeos and, you know, they should dress more modestly

01:01:46.560 --> 01:01:53.440
[Guest]: and so on. There's a response from these women of Bengal. Gandhi then writes a follow up

01:01:53.440 --> 01:01:59.960
[Guest]: where he quotes a little bit of that response and addresses it. Now in the Sabarmati archives,

01:01:59.960 --> 01:02:03.560
[Guest]: I found the entire response, the handwritten response, the wonderful letter, you know,

01:02:03.560 --> 01:02:08.160
[Guest]: it says 11 women of Bengal, and I quote much more than Gandhi does. And it is a brilliant

01:02:08.160 --> 01:02:13.880
[Guest]: feminist, you know, critique of male voyeurism, victim shaming, all the things that we talk

01:02:13.880 --> 01:02:18.840
[Guest]: about now, you know, and it's superbly written, but it's a great deal of intellectual rigor

01:02:18.840 --> 01:02:22.840
[Guest]: and self-confidence. And it's there in the Sabarmati archives, the whole thing, which

01:02:22.840 --> 01:02:28.020
[Guest]: is a joy to discover this, that in 1937, there were these women, you know, writing this kind

01:02:28.020 --> 01:02:29.020
[Guest]: of thing.

01:02:29.020 --> 01:02:36.040
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, it's his attitude to women is complicated. You know, he is, again, evolving.

01:02:36.040 --> 01:02:42.840
[Guest]: But again, I think he is, he must be given credit for bringing women into public life.

01:02:42.840 --> 01:02:46.880
[Guest]: You know, Madhu Kishwar, which is another name, you may be surprised to have me quote

01:02:46.880 --> 01:02:50.720
[Guest]: in this context, but I'll quote up positively and affirmatively, because there was a Madhu

01:02:50.720 --> 01:02:55.880
[Guest]: Kishwar before, there is today's Madhu Kishwar. Many years ago, she wrote a very good piece,

01:02:55.880 --> 01:03:00.920
[Guest]: you know, in her more sober scholarly avatar, which is what she was then. She wrote a first

01:03:00.920 --> 01:03:05.120
[Guest]: state piece in the EPW called Gandhi and Women, which kind of analyzed the contradictions

01:03:05.120 --> 01:03:11.480
[Guest]: in Gandhi's worldview. And while pointing to his patronizing attitude towards women,

01:03:11.480 --> 01:03:17.080
[Guest]: also says something quite striking. She said, Gandhi brought more women into public life

01:03:17.080 --> 01:03:22.600
[Guest]: than Mao, Lenin, Stalin, Churchill, de Gaulle, Roosevelt, which is absolutely true. I mean,

01:03:22.600 --> 01:03:29.320
[Guest]: in 1924, Gandhi comes out of jail. The Congress wants him as president. He says, no, Sarojini

01:03:29.320 --> 01:03:32.280
[Guest]: Naidu should be president. They said, no, you have to come be president because you

01:03:32.280 --> 01:03:36.520
[Guest]: have to reconcile the party. It's split between Swarajis and no changers. He said, okay. But

01:03:36.520 --> 01:03:39.360
[Guest]: next year, he insists that Sarojini Naidu is made president.

01:03:39.360 --> 01:03:40.360
[Amit Varma]: The first Indian born woman.

01:03:40.360 --> 01:03:46.360
[Guest]: And in 1925, it was inconceivable. There were no democratic women who were senators. Now

01:03:46.360 --> 01:03:49.540
[Guest]: you have Elizabeth Warren. I mean, now, of course, the USA is far ahead of us. But back

01:03:49.540 --> 01:03:52.880
[Guest]: in those days, you may not even have had a city council president who was a woman, right?

01:03:52.880 --> 01:03:57.160
[Guest]: And here you have the president of the major national party. Women participate in the Salt

01:03:57.160 --> 01:04:01.960
[Guest]: March and Quit India Movement. They're in the Congress Working Committee. So, which

01:04:01.960 --> 01:04:07.860
[Guest]: is, whereas, the Bolshevik revolution is largely, almost all male. Chinese communist movement

01:04:07.860 --> 01:04:14.880
[Guest]: is totally male. De Gaulle, Churchill, and so on are much more contemptuous of woman

01:04:14.880 --> 01:04:19.040
[Guest]: power and woman autonomy and dignity. This is not to defend Gandhi, but to contextualize

01:04:19.040 --> 01:04:25.380
[Guest]: it. That, you know, by the standards of today, he was wanting. By the standards of his time,

01:04:25.380 --> 01:04:29.000
[Guest]: he was in advance of other political leaders who were his contemporaries. I think that's

01:04:29.000 --> 01:04:31.520
[Amit Varma]: something which must be placed on record.

01:04:31.520 --> 01:04:37.640
[Amit Varma]: Now I want to move on to, you know, what I've labeled over here as obsessions. And, you

01:04:37.640 --> 01:04:42.800
[Amit Varma]: know, Gandhi's obsessions in a sense. And my favorite sentence in your whole book, excuse

01:04:42.800 --> 01:04:45.800
[Amit Varma]: me for saying this, but I'll have to quote it. My favorite sentence in your whole book,

01:04:45.800 --> 01:04:52.200
[Amit Varma]: which made me LOL, so to say, was, start quote, on 14th April, 1938, Gandhi awoke with an

01:04:52.200 --> 01:04:58.200
[Amit Varma]: erection and despite efforts to control his excitement, had a masturbatory experience.

01:04:58.200 --> 01:05:02.440
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote. And this is a very funny passage because then obviously the obsession in question,

01:05:02.440 --> 01:05:07.400
[Amit Varma]: which I'm talking about is celibacy and he's deeply disturbed by this. And he thinks of

01:05:07.400 --> 01:05:11.080
[Amit Varma]: even going public with it till, you know, Rajaji and all in alarm managed to stop him

01:05:11.080 --> 01:05:15.840
[Amit Varma]: and because he would of course be the butt of jokes if he went public with it. And, um,

01:05:15.840 --> 01:05:19.920
[Amit Varma]: and celibacy was one of his sort of personal improvement obsessions throughout his life.

01:05:19.920 --> 01:05:25.160
[Amit Varma]: He insisted that his children be celibate. He didn't let them marry. And, uh, he would

01:05:25.160 --> 01:05:30.000
[Amit Varma]: write editorials in the various magazines. He did talking about the importance of preserving

01:05:30.000 --> 01:05:33.160
[Amit Varma]: the vital fluids. Uh, I mean,

01:05:33.160 --> 01:05:37.400
[Guest]: No, it is, it is. I mean, this goes back to volume one where I talk about how he became

01:05:37.400 --> 01:05:41.760
[Guest]: a Brahmachari and you know, how he learned from Tolstoy and Raichand Bhai. Oh, he, how

01:05:41.760 --> 01:05:46.120
[Guest]: he followed them, not learned was, you know, convinced by the argument that Brahmacharya

01:05:46.120 --> 01:05:51.320
[Guest]: was crucial and preserving the vital fluids was also. And of course he carries on in India.

01:05:51.320 --> 01:05:55.680
[Guest]: I mean, I quote earlier, well before this episode of 1938, I quote some lectures he

01:05:55.680 --> 01:06:00.080
[Guest]: gave to his, uh, ashramites in the early twenties, where he said, you know, you have to preserve

01:06:00.080 --> 01:06:06.600
[Guest]: the semen and all of that. And very important. So there is some, uh, some kind of a irrational

01:06:06.600 --> 01:06:11.040
[Guest]: mumbo jumbo about all of this. Now, there was a paragraph in my book, which I cut out

01:06:11.040 --> 01:06:17.000
[Guest]: about that 1938 masturbatory experience, which is, I can recall now, because it's quite amusing.

01:06:17.000 --> 01:06:21.760
[Guest]: We know it was in Delhi. Now we don't know, but it's very likely it was in Gandhi's son's

01:06:21.760 --> 01:06:27.720
[Guest]: house. So he was having this experience in the house of his son, where there were three

01:06:27.720 --> 01:06:31.200
[Guest]: of his grandchildren also living now, which may have shamed him even more. You know that

01:06:31.200 --> 01:06:36.600
[Guest]: here is a elderly grandfather, you know, having this kind of experience, right? Now I didn't

01:06:36.600 --> 01:06:39.120
[Guest]: have evidence that it was the son's house. He could have been staying in a guest house.

01:06:39.120 --> 01:06:45.000
[Guest]: So I didn't put it in, but it is something that of course, uh, uh, much later in 1946,

01:06:45.000 --> 01:06:50.160
[Guest]: when he has, uh, the desire to test himself in Noah Khalil because he feels that his world

01:06:50.160 --> 01:06:56.480
[Guest]: is coming around him and he has this extraordinary, this is really self delusion. This is the

01:06:56.480 --> 01:07:00.040
[Guest]: greatest self delusion of Gandhi's life, that if he controls his sexual urges, Hindus and

01:07:00.040 --> 01:07:03.000
[Guest]: Muslims will stop butchering one another, which is how he feels in 1946.

01:07:03.000 --> 01:07:07.480
[Guest]: I mean, the reason he does those last experiments in Brahmacharya is that he feels that somehow

01:07:07.480 --> 01:07:11.320
[Guest]: he has failed and because he has failed, Hindus and Muslims are butchering one another. That

01:07:11.320 --> 01:07:17.200
[Guest]: is completely deluded, but it is, it is an extraordinary obsession. You know, this, the

01:07:17.200 --> 01:07:25.520
[Guest]: desire to control his sexuality and, uh, when they appear to be, uh, unbeating failures

01:07:25.520 --> 01:07:31.400
[Guest]: as in this masturbating experience, uh, the sense of guilt, self remorse, self flagellation

01:07:31.400 --> 01:07:33.360
[Amit Varma]: that overcomes him, you know, uh, is

01:07:33.360 --> 01:07:37.920
[Amit Varma]: No, when you talk about 1946, I mean, it's a, it's a stunning episode because he, he

01:07:37.920 --> 01:07:43.240
[Amit Varma]: calls his grand niece Manu with her father over and he says that, listen, I want to test

01:07:43.240 --> 01:07:47.080
[Amit Varma]: myself by sleeping on the same bed as you. And the reason for this is that Hindus and

01:07:47.080 --> 01:07:51.900
[Amit Varma]: Muslims need to stop killing each other. And this is the only way. And that just seems

01:07:51.900 --> 01:07:55.600
[Amit Varma]: very bizarre. And in the forties, there are a lot of bizarre things happening in the sense

01:07:55.600 --> 01:07:59.080
[Amit Varma]: another of his obsessions. I don't know if it's fair to call it an obsession because

01:07:59.080 --> 01:08:03.400
[Amit Varma]: it's also one of his great contributions to the world is the obsession with nonviolence.

01:08:03.400 --> 01:08:08.280
[Amit Varma]: And he actually, you know, before that in the thirties, he advises the Jews of Germany,

01:08:08.280 --> 01:08:12.760
[Amit Varma]: not to resist Hitler, to fight him with passive resistance. When the war starts, he wants

01:08:12.760 --> 01:08:18.720
[Amit Varma]: a British to abandon their glorious homes and let Hitler occupy them and do the whole

01:08:18.720 --> 01:08:23.240
[Amit Varma]: passive resistance things. He says the same kind of thing to Chiang Kai-shek. And you

01:08:23.240 --> 01:08:26.840
[Amit Varma]: know, by this time where he's in the seventies and the forties have begun first, he's telling

01:08:26.840 --> 01:08:31.280
[Amit Varma]: everyone to be nonviolent, you know, be nonviolent against Hitler, be nonviolent against Germany,

01:08:31.280 --> 01:08:36.380
[Amit Varma]: blah, blah, blah. On the other hand, all these experiments are going on. And if it was anyone

01:08:36.380 --> 01:08:40.840
[Amit Varma]: else without his enormous stature, you'd just be regarded as completely cuckoo.

01:08:40.840 --> 01:08:45.360
[Guest]: Yeah. Yeah. Yeah. But I think, you know, to go to return to the celibacy experiments,

01:08:45.360 --> 01:08:52.520
[Guest]: I think he is desperately lonely at this time. You know, he has no one to speak to. C.F.

01:08:52.520 --> 01:08:58.000
[Guest]: Andrews is dead. Tagore is dead. Mahadev is dead. Kasturba is dead. Jamnalal Bajaj, who

01:08:58.000 --> 01:09:03.480
[Guest]: was his adopted son, to whom he was close to the end of his own sons, is dead. And he's

01:09:03.480 --> 01:09:08.200
[Guest]: alone and lonely and confused in Bengal and does this completely nutty thing. Now, I'm

01:09:08.200 --> 01:09:12.000
[Guest]: sure Mahadev could have told him, you're crazy. Don't do this. Hindus and Muslims are butchering

01:09:12.000 --> 01:09:17.040
[Guest]: one another in spite of all you've done to stop it. It's not your failure. It's got nothing

01:09:17.040 --> 01:09:23.680
[Guest]: to do with your personal sexuality. But I think in that he was lonely, confused, and

01:09:23.680 --> 01:09:25.680
[Guest]: he succumbs to this bizarre delusion.

01:09:25.680 --> 01:09:30.280
[Amit Varma]: Great. So we need to wind up in 20 minutes. So what I'll do is I won't go back to the

01:09:30.280 --> 01:09:33.960
[Amit Varma]: narrative of the book. Instead, I'll urge all the listeners to just buy it and read

01:09:33.960 --> 01:09:38.420
[Amit Varma]: it because it's it's a fascinating story. And it's obviously all the spoilers are done

01:09:38.420 --> 01:09:42.320
[Amit Varma]: because it's history. And you know what happened, but it's incredibly fascinating. Anyway, I

01:09:42.320 --> 01:09:48.200
[Amit Varma]: just want to end with a bunch of sort of bigger questions about Gandhi and about India. Um,

01:09:48.200 --> 01:09:52.200
[Amit Varma]: question number one, you you quote a conversation he has with Meenu Masani, who's then a socialist

01:09:52.200 --> 01:09:56.800
[Amit Varma]: later becomes classical liberal, but then a socialist, where he tells Meenu Masani that

01:09:56.800 --> 01:10:01.640
[Amit Varma]: my objection to your socialism is coercion. Yeah, right, which seems very enlightened

01:10:01.640 --> 01:10:07.760
[Amit Varma]: and makes me happy. It seems almost libertarian. But, uh, and which he doesn't entirely follow

01:10:07.760 --> 01:10:13.840
[Amit Varma]: in his own life or prescriptions or whatever, because a lot of his, but one of the things

01:10:13.840 --> 01:10:19.000
[Amit Varma]: that does stand out about Gandhi from a lot of big leaders is that he privileges the means

01:10:19.000 --> 01:10:25.960
[Amit Varma]: over the end. You know, he's, is that something that made its mark in Indian life and Indian

01:10:25.960 --> 01:10:26.960
[Guest]: thought?

01:10:26.960 --> 01:10:33.240
[Guest]: I think he's that sets him apart from, you know, political leaders everywhere, not just

01:10:33.240 --> 01:10:38.160
[Guest]: in India, but before I come to just go back to Meenu Masani, there's a line that would

01:10:38.160 --> 01:10:42.880
[Guest]: have gotten you when you read it was when Meenu Masani, who's then a fervent socialist

01:10:42.880 --> 01:10:47.600
[Guest]: presents him the manifesto of the Congress Socialist Party in 1934. And it says, when

01:10:47.600 --> 01:10:52.480
[Guest]: we come to power, we will nationalize all instruments of production. And Gandhi says,

01:10:52.480 --> 01:10:58.960
[Guest]: Rabindranath Tagore is a marvel and instrument of production. Will you nationalize it? Brilliant.

01:10:58.960 --> 01:11:03.960
[Guest]: That is totally brilliant. Right. So, you know, all freedom of all kinds, including

01:11:03.960 --> 01:11:08.320
[Guest]: a study of expression is going to be subject to Stalinist control and nationalization.

01:11:08.320 --> 01:11:14.920
[Guest]: You know, uh, I mean, I mean, they're kind of, uh, uh, there are three kinds of politicians.

01:11:14.920 --> 01:11:20.200
[Guest]: One is kind of divided, you know, uh, and I think Modi and Indira Gandhi fall into that

01:11:20.200 --> 01:11:25.400
[Guest]: divided category of people who want power for its own sake, but also by their own lights

01:11:25.400 --> 01:11:30.040
[Guest]: think they want to do good. Right. That's one category. Another category is who just

01:11:30.040 --> 01:11:34.960
[Guest]: want power and want to exercise it ruthlessly, immorally. And, uh, you know, Amit Shah would

01:11:34.960 --> 01:11:40.240
[Guest]: fall in that category and probably many African dictators and so on and so forth. Right. Now,

01:11:40.240 --> 01:11:45.760
[Guest]: Gandhi is someone who of course has a great capacity to be pragmatic, to compromise, but

01:11:45.760 --> 01:11:49.680
[Guest]: on some issues, he will not compromise. On some moral issues. And we discussed this again

01:11:49.680 --> 01:11:55.400
[Guest]: in the first episode, nonviolence and Hindu Muslim harmony are for him absolutely, you

01:11:55.400 --> 01:12:03.360
[Guest]: know, sacrosanct. And also finally, he would want before launching a nonviolent movement

01:12:03.360 --> 01:12:09.320
[Guest]: to keep all the avenues of communication, of conciliation, of negotiation open. So till

01:12:09.320 --> 01:12:14.920
[Guest]: the last moment he would want to discuss with the viceroy. Uh, and I think this is all with

01:12:14.920 --> 01:12:19.440
[Guest]: Ambedkar or with Jinnah, you know, he would keep channels open all the time. I think these

01:12:19.440 --> 01:12:24.040
[Guest]: are ways in which he really differs from people who take more hard line stance.

01:12:24.040 --> 01:12:28.480
[Amit Varma]: My second question, and this is often raised, is that, do you think that these individuals

01:12:28.480 --> 01:12:31.800
[Amit Varma]: were really so consequential or would India have gotten independence anyway? I mean, the

01:12:31.800 --> 01:12:34.200
[Amit Varma]: British were practically bankrupt after the war and so on.

01:12:34.200 --> 01:12:38.640
[Guest]: No, we got a different kind of independence. And I think that several respects in which,

01:12:38.640 --> 01:12:43.160
[Guest]: I mean, I think many aspects of the constitution, though people claim is borrowed from, you

01:12:43.160 --> 01:12:48.320
[Guest]: know, the 35 constitution and so on, or many aspects of, uh, political practice. And again,

01:12:48.320 --> 01:12:53.600
[Guest]: we discussed this in our first episode. So federalism, you know, uh, this is whole, uh,

01:12:53.600 --> 01:13:00.800
[Guest]: I have, uh, uh, for the last five years, uh, from before Narendra Modi came to power, telling

01:13:00.800 --> 01:13:07.680
[Guest]: warning against apocalyptic talk about fascism, because I believe that, uh, federalism will

01:13:07.680 --> 01:13:12.280
[Guest]: save India, you know, from authoritarian rule, you know, so, and we owe federalism, including

01:13:12.280 --> 01:13:14.040
[Guest]: linguistic federalism to Gandhi.

01:13:14.040 --> 01:13:22.600
[Guest]: Now, so I think the sense of debate, dialogue, pluralism, we would have had, and also social

01:13:22.600 --> 01:13:27.400
[Guest]: reform, I mean, equality for women and Dalits, at least under the law, not in everyday life.

01:13:27.400 --> 01:13:31.080
[Guest]: I mean, it's still denied in everyday life. We don't have equal rights in everyday life.

01:13:31.080 --> 01:13:34.840
[Guest]: Dalits in outside the cities and sometimes not even in the cities have equal rights in

01:13:34.840 --> 01:13:40.280
[Guest]: everyday life. But I think these are ways in which Gandhi prepared us for a much more

01:13:40.280 --> 01:13:47.800
[Guest]: meaningful freedom than Aurobindo Ghosh or Subhash Chandra Bose or Bhagat Singh or Veer

01:13:47.800 --> 01:13:51.960
[Guest]: Savarkar or any of the other currently fashionable icons could have brought us.

01:13:51.960 --> 01:13:56.240
[Amit Varma]: Right. So my final question, which is a slightly complicated question, and it's a three part

01:13:56.240 --> 01:14:02.960
[Amit Varma]: question, uh, which is basic, the basic big question is how would Gandhi have reacted

01:14:02.960 --> 01:14:07.840
[Amit Varma]: to India as it is today? And I'll break it up into three parts. One is, would he have

01:14:07.840 --> 01:14:12.640
[Amit Varma]: seen a resonance between the British empire that he fought against and the modern Indian

01:14:12.640 --> 01:14:17.600
[Amit Varma]: state? For example, many of the laws under which he was arrested, 124A which is sedition,

01:14:17.600 --> 01:14:24.200
[Amit Varma]: 153A, 295A still exist and are still regularly used for political purposes. He protested

01:14:24.200 --> 01:14:28.160
[Amit Varma]: the salt tax in Gandhi famously, but the salt tax today is many times more than what it

01:14:28.160 --> 01:14:33.400
[Amit Varma]: was then. In fact, you could argue that taxation as a whole is far more oppressive and so on.

01:14:33.400 --> 01:14:37.600
[Amit Varma]: So one is at the level, how would he have thought about a parallel between the oppression

01:14:37.600 --> 01:14:41.320
[Amit Varma]: that you got from the British empire and the oppression that you got from your own rulers?

01:14:41.320 --> 01:14:47.160
[Guest]: So I think 124A and those other acts, he clearly says in young India, 1929, I think if memory

01:14:47.160 --> 01:14:52.040
[Guest]: serves, he says, when we come to power, we will remove 124A. He says that clearly that

01:14:52.040 --> 01:14:56.640
[Guest]: hasn't happened. In fact, many ways it's become more arbitrary, you know, the misuse of, of

01:14:56.640 --> 01:15:00.240
[Guest]: those laws. I mean, the recent arrest of the journalist in Manipur and many other examples

01:15:00.240 --> 01:15:06.600
[Guest]: of that kind. Now economics, it's more complicated. You know, I think Gandhi is to be trusted

01:15:06.600 --> 01:15:12.640
[Guest]: in many ways, but perhaps not so much as an economist. I think his suspicion of the excessive

01:15:12.640 --> 01:15:19.120
[Guest]: powers accruing to the state, whether in regulating everyday life or in regulating the economy,

01:15:19.120 --> 01:15:24.800
[Guest]: I think are salutary and Rajaji takes those forward in his own formation of the Sandhya

01:15:24.800 --> 01:15:29.800
[Guest]: Party. But on sedition, he explicitly says that when we come to power, 124 and 124A will

01:15:29.800 --> 01:15:32.640
[Guest]: go and they haven't gone 70 years later.

01:15:32.640 --> 01:15:37.840
[Amit Varma]: Okay. The second part of the three part question is a thought experiment. If he was a young

01:15:37.840 --> 01:15:42.160
[Amit Varma]: Kashmiri today, would he fight for Kashmir's independence? Because you could make the same

01:15:42.160 --> 01:15:46.440
[Amit Varma]: case for Kashmir's independence against people they see as a foreign occupying power and

01:15:46.440 --> 01:15:50.560
[Amit Varma]: behave pretty brutally as an Indian would in those days against the British empire,

01:15:50.560 --> 01:15:53.920
[Amit Varma]: which was an occupying power and which didn't even always behave that brutally.

01:15:53.920 --> 01:16:01.160
[Guest]: Look, I, it's hard to say. I can only say that when Gandhi died in 1948, the first Kashmir

01:16:01.160 --> 01:16:04.640
[Guest]: war had just begun and he took the side of the Indian army. In fact, unlike in the case

01:16:04.640 --> 01:16:10.280
[Guest]: of his advice to the Jews to resist Hitler non-violently, in 1948, he said this is an

01:16:10.280 --> 01:16:13.480
[Guest]: unfair incursion by the Pakistanis and we must resist it. So he supported the Indian

01:16:13.480 --> 01:16:17.200
[Guest]: army. Much has changed since then. I mean, that was a different Kashmir with Sheikh Abdullah

01:16:17.200 --> 01:16:20.400
[Guest]: who was generally secular and so on and so forth.

01:16:20.400 --> 01:16:29.080
[Guest]: Today, you know, I think the position of Rajaji, which I've described at great length in India

01:16:29.080 --> 01:16:32.640
[Guest]: after Gandhi, the peace proposal that he held out, which Nehru accepted just before Nehru

01:16:32.640 --> 01:16:36.880
[Guest]: died and then, you know, Sheikh Abdullah went to, was released under that peace proposal

01:16:36.880 --> 01:16:42.200
[Guest]: in 1964 and went to meet Ayub Khan and so on, which is a kind of confederation, India-Pakistan-Kashmir

01:16:42.200 --> 01:16:47.840
[Guest]: confederation, you know, soft borders, you know, the kind of Manmohan Singh line of soft

01:16:47.840 --> 01:16:54.280
[Guest]: borders, no change in line of control, greater autonomy to Kashmiris on either side of the

01:16:54.280 --> 01:16:58.880
[Guest]: border. I don't think you're an advocate of independence. I think independence opens

01:16:58.880 --> 01:17:03.760
[Guest]: a Pandora's box of different kinds. You know, he said, we must as Indians, certainly he

01:17:03.760 --> 01:17:07.880
[Guest]: would oppose pellet guns, pellet guns to the Kashmiris when the Jats and the Gujars and

01:17:07.880 --> 01:17:12.280
[Guest]: the Patidars are treated, you know, with water cannons, you know.

01:17:12.280 --> 01:17:16.320
[Amit Varma]: Maybe he'd have begun as he began in South Africa anyway, as a moderate petitioning and

01:17:16.320 --> 01:17:18.160
[Guest]: trying to work within the system.

01:17:18.160 --> 01:17:23.360
[Guest]: Because Kashmir is very complicated and, you know, Kashmir is a situation in which I've

01:17:23.360 --> 01:17:29.760
[Guest]: thought about very deeply and, you know, and I've written about also at some length and,

01:17:29.760 --> 01:17:35.600
[Guest]: you know, the Indian state has much to answer for, the Pakistani state has much to answer

01:17:35.600 --> 01:17:42.000
[Guest]: for, but so do the Jihadis of Kashmir. I mean, what happened to the Kashmiri Pandits is unconscionable.

01:17:42.000 --> 01:17:50.400
[Guest]: They were purged and expelled and no amount of, you know, euphemism can, you know, excuse

01:17:50.400 --> 01:17:55.960
[Guest]: that. I mean, this, the Indian left is in denial about, forget the, the Indian left

01:17:55.960 --> 01:17:59.880
[Guest]: is in denial, the Kashmiris are in denial about how they treated the Pandits.

01:17:59.880 --> 01:18:04.560
[Guest]: And I think the moral case for Kashmiri independence absolutely evaporated once they kicked out

01:18:04.560 --> 01:18:09.600
[Guest]: the Pandits. So, and I think Gandhi would have recognized that. I mean, the treatment

01:18:09.600 --> 01:18:16.720
[Guest]: of everywhere else in India, Muslims are insecure, vulnerable, occasionally persecuted, but

01:18:16.720 --> 01:18:23.280
[Guest]: in one state of the union, Kashmir, it's the Hindus who are insecure, persecuted, marginalized

01:18:23.280 --> 01:18:30.600
[Guest]: and expelled. So I think that the moral case for Kashmiri independence absolutely disappeared

01:18:30.600 --> 01:18:37.080
[Guest]: when not only were they thrown out, not a single leader of the Kashmiri freedom struggle

01:18:37.080 --> 01:18:46.040
[Guest]: atoned for it. They were in 1989, they fled. It took 15 years for the so-called moderate

01:18:46.040 --> 01:18:54.400
[Guest]: among the Kashmiri Huriyat, like the Maulvi Farooq to go and to a Pandit camp in Jammu

01:18:54.400 --> 01:18:58.000
[Guest]: and he probably only went once and God knows that he's never gone back again. So I think

01:18:58.000 --> 01:19:02.400
[Guest]: the moral case for Kashmiri independence disappeared once the Pandits were expelled and the way

01:19:02.400 --> 01:19:03.920
[Amit Varma]: in which they were expelled.

01:19:03.920 --> 01:19:07.880
[Amit Varma]: That's fascinating. And we should do an episode on that sometime, if you're willing. The last

01:19:07.880 --> 01:19:12.280
[Amit Varma]: part of the last question is that if Gandhi was in this modern world and he was notoriously

01:19:12.280 --> 01:19:17.560
[Amit Varma]: suspicious of modernity with technology, medicine, machinery, all of those things, and if he

01:19:17.560 --> 01:19:21.600
[Amit Varma]: was alive today in the world of Twitter, say here a Twitter account, what would he be like?

01:19:21.600 --> 01:19:22.600
[Amit Varma]: What would he be fighting for?

01:19:22.600 --> 01:19:28.840
[Guest]: Well, let me answer that very elliptically and cryptically in the words of Shiv Vishwanathan.

01:19:28.840 --> 01:19:36.880
[Guest]: Shiv Vishwanathan once wrote, Gandhi famously said, when he visited England in 1931, what

01:19:36.880 --> 01:19:40.920
[Guest]: would you think of Western civilization? And he said, I think it would be a good idea.

01:19:40.920 --> 01:19:44.400
[Guest]: Now, if he came back to India and was asked, what do you think of Indian civilization? He

01:19:44.400 --> 01:19:47.080
[Guest]: would say that too would be a good idea.

